    {'id':'y2-t4-w1-l4','year':'Y2','term':'T4',     'week':1,'weekLesson':4,     'sequence':'Sequence 7','lesson':'Lesson 1',     'focus':'Adding –s after y',     'explanation':'These rules apply to nouns and verbs.\nWhen the word ends in a vowel + y, we simply add the letter ‘s’ to the end of the word.\nFor example, the word donkey becomes donkeys.\nWhen a word ends in a consonant + y, we must first change the letter ‘y’ to an ‘i’ before we add -es.\nFor example, the word carry becomes carries.\nWhen applying these rules to nouns, we are forming a plural noun (e.g. keys) from a singular noun (e.g. key).',     'hlWords':['justify', 'try', 'deny', 'supply', 'apply', 'donkey', 'turkey', 'valley', 'honey', 'chimney']},
