    {'id':'y2-t4-w4-l1','year':'Y2','term':'T4',     'week':4,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':'Mastery 4','lesson':'Lesson 1',     'focus':'/o/ spelt  a after w and qu',     'explanation':'The /o/ phoneme is often spelt with an a following a w or qu. For example, in the words: wash, want, quality and quad. This \nis because w and qu can change how vowel sounds are pronounced.',     'hlWords':['ladies', 'surveys', 'holidays', 'libraries', 'fries', 'stories', 'cherries', 'cities', 'carries', 'parties']},
    {'id':'y2-t4-w4-l2','year':'Y2','term':'T4',     'week':4,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':'Mastery 4','lesson':'Lesson 2',     'focus':'/o/ spelt a after w or qu',     'explanation':'The /o/ phoneme is often spelt with an a following a w or qu. For example, in the words: wash, want, quality and quad. This \nis because w and qu can change how vowel sounds are pronounced.',     'hlWords':['copying', 'crying', 'hurrying', 'marrying', 'frying', 'carrying', 'replying', 'flying', 'studying', 'worrying']},
    {'id':'y2-t4-w4-l3','year':'Y2','term':'T4',     'week':4,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':'Mastery 5','lesson':'Lesson 1',     'focus':'/igh/ spelt  y & /ee/ spelt ey',     'explanation':'The /igh/ phoneme is spelt igh when the /igh/ sound is in the middle of a word and followed by a consonant (often a t). For \nexample, in the words light and sight.\nThe /igh/ phoneme is often spelt y at the end of a short, one syllable word. For example, in the words my, fly and sky. \nHowever, it can also be used at the end of longer, multi-syllabic words such as; apply and justify.\nThe /ee/ phoneme is usually spelt ey at the end of a word. These words are often two-syllable words, for example; jockey, \nchimney and valley.',     'hlWords':['happier', 'lazier', 'dirtier', 'funnier', 'trickiest', 'angrier', 'tidier', 'busier', 'funniest', 'luckier']},
    {'id':'y2-t4-w4-l4','year':'Y2','term':'T4',     'week':4,'weekLesson':4,     'sequence':'Mastery 5','lesson':'Lesson 2',     'focus':'/igh/ spelt  y & /ee/ spelt ey',     'explanation':'The /igh/ phoneme is spelt igh when the /igh/ sound is in the middle of a word and followed by a consonant (often a t). For \nexample, in the words light and sight.\nThe /igh/ phoneme is often spelt y at the end of a short, one syllable word. For example, in the words my, fly and sky. \nHowever, it can also be used at the end of longer, multi-syllabic words such as; apply and justify.\nThe /ee/ phoneme is usually spelt ey at the end of a word. These words are often two-syllable words, for example; jockey, \nchimney and valley.',     'hlWords':['hurrying', 'lazier', 'busiest', 'carried', 'dirtier', 'smelliest', 'worrying', 'tidied', 'cried', 'copying']},
    {'id':'y2-t4-w4-l5','year':'Y2','term':'T4',     'week':4,'weekLesson':5,     'sequence':'Mastery 6','lesson':'Lesson 1',     'focus':'Words ending in -le/-el/-al/-il',     'explanation':'The -le ending is the most commonly used of the endings in this unit.\nIt usually follows a consonant (other than those listed for the -el ending).\nThe -le ending is usually used when the last syllable of the word is unstressed.\nThe -el ending is often used after the letters m, n, r, s, v or w.\nExamples of these include camel, tunnel, squirrel, tinsel, travel and towel.\nThe -al ending is often applied when the word is an adjective.\nAn example of this would include magical (where the noun magic has formed the adjective magical).\nThere is no clear rule for the application of the -il ending (e.g.',     'hlWords':['moving', 'baking', 'driving', 'closing', 'escaping', 'using', 'smiling', 'coming', 'hoping', 'riding']},
    {'id':'y2-t4-w5-l1','year':'Y2','term':'T4',     'week':5,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':'Mastery 6','lesson':'Lesson 2',     'focus':'Words ending in -le/-el/-al/-il',     'explanation':'The -le ending is the most commonly used of the endings in this unit.\nIt usually follows a consonant (other than those listed for the -el ending).\nThe -le ending is usually used when the last syllable of the word is unstressed.\nThe -el ending is often used after the letters m, n, r, s, v or w.\nExamples of these include camel, tunnel, squirrel, tinsel, travel and towel.\nThe -al ending is often applied when the word is an adjective.\nAn example of this would include magical (where the noun magic has formed the adjective magical).\nThere is no clear rule for the application of the -il ending (e.g.',     'hlWords':['closed', 'closer', 'closest', 'braver', 'bravest', 'cutest', 'used', 'moved', 'wiser', 'finest']},
    {'id':'y2-t4-w5-l2','year':'Y2','term':'T4',     'week':5,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':'Mastery 7','lesson':'Lesson 1',     'focus':'Adding –es after y',     'explanation':'These rules apply to nouns and verbs.\nWhen the word ends in a vowel + y, we simply add the letter ‘s’ to the end of the word.\nFor example, the word donkey becomes donkeys.\nWhen a word ends in a consonant + y, we must first change the letter ‘y’ to an ‘i’ before we add -es.\nFor example, the word carry becomes carries.\nWhen applying these rules to nouns, we are forming a plural noun (e.g. keys) from a singular noun (e.g. key).',     'hlWords':['safest', 'smoky', 'slimy', 'braver', 'noticed', 'waving', 'spicy', 'tasty', 'shiny', 'icy']},
    {'id':'y2-t4-w5-l3','year':'Y2','term':'T4',     'week':5,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':'Mastery 7','lesson':'Lesson 2',     'focus':'Adding –es after y',     'explanation':'These rules apply to nouns and verbs.\nWhen the word ends in a vowel + y, we simply add the letter ‘s’ to the end of the word.\nFor example, the word donkey becomes donkeys.\nWhen a word ends in a consonant + y, we must first change the letter ‘y’ to an ‘i’ before we add -es.\nFor example, the word carry becomes carries.\nWhen applying these rules to nouns, we are forming a plural noun (e.g. keys) from a singular noun (e.g. key).',     'hlWords':['tapping', 'stopped', 'thinnest', 'patting', 'flipped', 'sitting', 'winner', 'runny', 'bigger', 'beginning']},
    {'id':'y2-t4-w5-l4','year':'Y2','term':'T4',     'week':5,'weekLesson':4,     'sequence':'Mastery 8','lesson':'Lesson 1',     'focus':'adding vowel suffixes after consonant + y',     'explanation':'When a word ends in a vowel + y, we simply add the vowel suffix.\nFor example, play becomes playing or played or player.\nWhen a word ends in a consonant + y, we simply add the -ing suffix.\nFor example, carry becomes carrying and reply becomes replying.\nThis rule changes when adding the suffixes -ed, -er and -est.\nFor these suffixes, when a word ends in a consonant + y, we change the y to i before we add the suffix.\nFor example, the word carry becomes carried and the word happy becomes happier.\nWhen a word ends in a consonant + e, we remove the e before we add a vowel suffix (-ed/-est/-er/-ing/',     'hlWords':['tallest', 'swimmer', 'dragged', 'nodding', 'slippy', 'bumpy', 'kinder', 'saddest', 'bumped', 'yelped']},
    {'id':'y2-t4-w5-l5','year':'Y2','term':'T4',     'week':5,'weekLesson':5,     'sequence':'Mastery 8','lesson':'Lesson 2',     'focus':'adding vowel suffixes after consonant + y',     'explanation':'When a word ends in a vowel + y, we simply add the vowel suffix.\nFor example, play becomes playing or played or player.\nWhen a word ends in a consonant + y, we simply add the -ing suffix.\nFor example, carry becomes carrying and reply becomes replying.\nThis rule changes when adding the suffixes -ed, -er and -est.\nFor these suffixes, when a word ends in a consonant + y, we change the y to i before we add the suffix.\nFor example, the word carry becomes carried and the word happy becomes happier.\nWhen a word ends in a consonant + e, we remove the e before we add a vowel suffix (-ed/-est/-er/-ing/',     'hlWords':['beeped', 'floated', 'trained', 'sweetest', 'fattest', 'dreamy', 'speaking', 'rainy', 'packed', 'cleanest']},
    {'id':'y2-t5-w1-l1','year':'Y2','term':'T5',     'week':1,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':'Sequence 11','lesson':'Lesson 1',     'focus':'Adding the suffix -ful',     'explanation':'The suffix ‘ful’ means “full of”. \nFor example, helpful means full of help, careful means full of care and joyful means full of joy.\nWe add –ful to the end of a root word. \nThe spelling of the root word usually stays the same.\n-ful is always spelt with only one l.',     'hlWords':['inviting', 'hiding', 'hoped', 'writer', 'making', 'baking', 'timing', 'driving', 'smiling', 'moved']},
    {'id':'y2-t5-w1-l2','year':'Y2','term':'T5',     'week':1,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':'Sequence 11','lesson':'Lesson 2',     'focus':'Adding the suffix -less',     'explanation':'The suffix ‘ful’ means “full of”. \nFor example, helpful means full of help, careful means full of care and joyful means full of joy.\nWe add –ful to the end of a root word. \nThe spelling of the root word usually stays the same.\n-ful is always spelt with only one l.\nThe suffix ‘less’ means ‘without’.\nFor example, careless means without care, fearless means without fear and harmless means without harm.\nWe add – less to the end of a root word.\nThe spelling of the root word usually stays the same.\n-less is always spelt with two s letters.',     'hlWords':['flamed', 'bravest', 'coming', 'tasty', 'hoping', 'riding', 'using', 'cared', 'finest', 'spicy']},
    {'id':'y2-t5-w1-l3','year':'Y2','term':'T5',     'week':1,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':'Sequence 11','lesson':'Lesson 3',     'focus':'Adding the suffix –ful and -less',     'explanation':'The suffix ‘ful’ means “full of”. \nFor example, helpful means full of help, careful means full of care and joyful means full of joy.\nWe add –ful to the end of a root word. \nThe spelling of the root word usually stays the same.\n-ful is always spelt with only one l.\nThe suffix ‘less’ means ‘without’.\nFor example, careless means without care, fearless means without fear and harmless means without harm.\nWe add – less to the end of a root word.\nThe spelling of the root word usually stays the same.\n-less is always spelt with two s letters.',     'hlWords':['tapped', 'hummed', 'stopped', 'tapping', 'humming', 'stopping', 'winning', 'muddy', 'biggest', 'sitting']},
    {'id':'y2-t5-w1-l4','year':'Y2','term':'T5',     'week':1,'weekLesson':4,     'sequence':'Sequence 12','lesson':'Lesson 1',     'focus':'Adding the suffix -ment',     'explanation':'The suffix ‘ment’ turns a verb into a noun. \nIt usually means: \n-The act of doing something\n-The result of an action\n-The state of something.\nFor example, the verb improve changes to the noun improvement and the verb enjoy changes to the noun enjoyment.\nNo change is needed to the spelling of the root word.',     'hlWords':['softer', 'thicker', 'stronger', 'softest', 'thickest', 'strongest', 'frothy', 'winner', 'treated', 'wagged']},
    {'id':'y2-t5-w1-l5','year':'Y2','term':'T5',     'week':1,'weekLesson':5,     'sequence':'Sequence 12','lesson':'Lesson 2',     'focus':'Adding the suffix –ment & -ness',     'explanation':'The suffix ‘ment’ turns a verb into a noun. \nIt usually means: \n-The act of doing something\n-The result of an action\n-The state of something.\nFor example, the verb ‘improve’ changes to the noun ‘improvement’ and the verb ‘enjoy’ changes to the noun ‘enjoyment’.\nNo change is needed to the spelling of the root word.\nThe suffix ‘ness’ turns an adjective into a noun. It shows the stage, quality or condition of something.\nFor example, the adjective ‘kind’ turns into ‘kindness’ meaning the quality of being kind.\nIf the adjective ends in a consonant + y, change the y to I before adding –ness. \nIf th',     'hlWords':['thankful', 'thankless', 'colourful', 'colourless', 'meaningful', 'meaningless', 'restless', 'useful', 'peaceful', 'hopeful']},
    {'id':'y2-t5-w2-l1','year':'Y2','term':'T5',     'week':2,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':'Sequence 12','lesson':'Lesson 3',     'focus':'Adding the suffix –ment, -ness & -ly',     'explanation':'The suffix ‘ment’ turns a verb into a noun. \nIt usually means: \n-The act of doing something\n-The result of an action\n-The state of something.\nFor example, the verb ‘improve’ changes to the noun ‘improvement’ and the verb ‘enjoy’ changes to the noun ‘enjoyment’.\nNo change is needed to the spelling of the root word.\nThe suffix ‘ness’ turns an adjective into a noun. It shows the stage, quality or condition of something.\nFor example, the adjective ‘kind’ turns into ‘kindness’ meaning the quality of being kind.\nIf the adjective ends in a consonant + y, change the y to I before adding –ness. \nIf th',     'hlWords':['painful', 'painless', 'wasteful', 'wishful', 'timeless', 'restless', 'wonderful', 'helpful', 'careful', 'fearless']},
    {'id':'y2-t5-w2-l2','year':'Y2','term':'T5',     'week':2,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':'Sequence 13','lesson':'Lesson 1',     'focus':'contractions',     'explanation':'Apostrophes can be used for two reasons: contractions and possession.\nWhen we combine two words to form a contraction, the apostrophe is used to replace the missing letter(s).\nFor example, when we combine do + not, we omit the second letter ‘o’. \nTherefore, this is where the apostrophe is placed – don’t.\nWhen we use apostrophes for possession, we need to consider who the ‘owner’ is.\nThis is an example sentence:\nI borrowed the teacher’s book.\nIn this sentence, the book is ‘owned’ by the teacher. \nTherefore, we place the apostrophe in the word teacher’s.\nThe apostrophe is placed before the lett',     'hlWords':['happiness', 'excitement', 'kindness', 'tiredness', 'commitment', 'enjoyment', 'improvement', 'sadness', 'darkness', 'movement']},
