    {'id':'y2-t5-w3-l3','year':'Y2','term':'T5',     'week':3,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':'Sequence 15','lesson':'Lesson 1',     'focus':'Words ending -tion',     'explanation':'When we add –tion to a verb it changes it into a noun. It usually means “the act” or “the result”.\nIf the word already ends in ‘t’ just add ‘ion’ (together it looks like ‘tion’).\nFor example, act \uf0e0action and invent \uf0e0invention.\nIf the word ends in ‘te’ drop the ‘e’ and add ‘ion’.\nFor example, promote \uf0e0promotion.\nOther less-common rules:\nIf the word ends in ‘ite’, change it to ‘ation’.\nFor example, invite \uf0e0invitation.\nIf the word ends in ‘ify’, change it to  ‘ification’.\nFor example, simplify \uf0e0simplification and classify \uf0e0classification.\nIf the word ends in ‘ise’, drop the ‘e’ and add ‘isation’',     'hlWords':['careful', 'careless', 'helpful', 'helpless', 'useful', 'useless', 'restful', 'restless', 'playful', 'fearless']},
