    {'id':'y2-t5-w4-l1','year':'Y2','term':'T5',     'week':4,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':'Mastery 9','lesson':'Lesson 1',     'focus':'adding vowel suffixes after consonant + e',     'explanation':'When a word ends in a consonant + e, we remove the e before we add a vowel suffix (-ed/-est/-er/-ing/-y).\nFor example, the word move becomes moving and the word shine becomes shiny.',     'hlWords':['quickly', 'loudly', 'carefully', 'poorly', 'clearly', 'busily', 'kindness', 'darkness', 'enjoyment', 'movement']},
    {'id':'y2-t5-w4-l2','year':'Y2','term':'T5',     'week':4,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':'Mastery 9','lesson':'Lesson 2',     'focus':'adding vowel suffixes after consonant + e',     'explanation':'When a word ends in a consonant + e, we remove the e before we add a vowel suffix (-ed/-est/-er/-ing/-y).\nFor example, the word move becomes moving and the word shine becomes shiny.',     'hlWords':["they're", "she's", "didn't", "shouldn't", "hadn't", "you're", "it's", "there's", "don't", "can't"]},
    {'id':'y2-t5-w4-l3','year':'Y2','term':'T5',     'week':4,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':'Mastery 10','lesson':'Lesson 1',     'focus':'Doubling consonants when adding suffixes',     'explanation':'This rule is complex because it contains several considerations and skills:\n1.\nThe number of syllables in the word\n2.\nThe final two letters of the word\n3.\nKnowledge of vowels and consonants\n4.\nKnowledge of vowel suffixes\nFor the purposes of vowel suffix rules, the letter ‘y’ is considered a vowel when applied as a suffix.\nWhen a word with one syllable ends in a single short vowel + consonant, we double the consonant before \nadding the vowel suffix (-ed/-ing/-er/-est/-y).\nFor example, the word jump ends in consonant + consonant.\nTherefore, we do not double the consonant (e.g. jumped or jumping',     'hlWords':["we've", "he'll", "you've", "we're", "they'll", "that'll", "she'll", "you'll", "it's", "didn't"]},
    {'id':'y2-t5-w4-l4','year':'Y2','term':'T5',     'week':4,'weekLesson':4,     'sequence':'Mastery 10','lesson':'Lesson 2',     'focus':'Doubling consonants when adding suffixes',     'explanation':'This rule is complex because it contains several considerations and skills:\n1.\nThe number of syllables in the word\n2.\nThe final two letters of the word\n3.\nKnowledge of vowels and consonants\n4.\nKnowledge of vowel suffixes\nFor the purposes of vowel suffix rules, the letter ‘y’ is considered a vowel when applied as a suffix.\nWhen a word with one syllable ends in a single short vowel + consonant, we double the consonant before \nadding the vowel suffix (-ed/-ing/-er/-est/-y).\nFor example, the word jump ends in consonant + consonant.\nTherefore, we do not double the consonant (e.g. jumped or jumping',     'hlWords':["they're", "we'll", "it's", "isn't", "could've", "don't", "can't", "she's", "he'll", "we've"]},
    {'id':'y2-t5-w4-l5','year':'Y2','term':'T5',     'week':4,'weekLesson':5,     'sequence':'Mastery 11','lesson':'Lesson 1',     'focus':'Adding the suffix –ful and -less',     'explanation':'The suffix ‘ful’ means “full of”. \nFor example, helpful means full of help, careful means full of care and joyful means full of joy.\nWe add –ful to the end of a root word. \nThe spelling of the root word usually stays the same.\n-ful is always spelt with only one l.\nThe suffix ‘less’ means ‘without’.\nFor example, careless means without care, fearless means without fear and harmless means without harm.\nWe add – less to the end of a root word.\nThe spelling of the root word usually stays the same.\n-less is always spelt with two s letters.',     'hlWords':["cat's", "dog's", "teacher's", "doctor's", "tree's", "bird's", "child's", "mum's", "girl's", "boy's"]},
    {'id':'y2-t5-w5-l1','year':'Y2','term':'T5',     'week':5,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':'Mastery 11','lesson':'Lesson 2',     'focus':'Adding the suffix –ful and -less',     'explanation':'The suffix ‘ful’ means “full of”. \nFor example, helpful means full of help, careful means full of care and joyful means full of joy.\nWe add –ful to the end of a root word. \nThe spelling of the root word usually stays the same.\n-ful is always spelt with only one l.\nThe suffix ‘less’ means ‘without’.\nFor example, careless means without care, fearless means without fear and harmless means without harm.\nWe add – less to the end of a root word.\nThe spelling of the root word usually stays the same.\n-less is always spelt with two s letters.',     'hlWords':["phone's", "group's", "city's", "queen's", "lion's", "school's", "friend's", "baby's", "rabbit's", "sun's"]},
    {'id':'y2-t5-w5-l2','year':'Y2','term':'T5',     'week':5,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':'Mastery 12','lesson':'Lesson 1',     'focus':'Adding the suffix –ment & -ness',     'explanation':'The suffix ‘ment’ turns a verb into a noun. \nIt usually means: \n-The act of doing something\n-The result of an action\n-The state of something.\nFor example, the verb ‘improve’ changes to the noun ‘improvement’ and the verb ‘enjoy’ changes to the noun ‘enjoyment’.\nNo change is needed to the spelling of the root word.\nThe suffix ‘ness’ turns an adjective into a noun. It shows the stage, quality or condition of something.\nFor example, the adjective ‘kind’ turns into ‘kindness’ meaning the quality of being kind.\nIf the adjective ends in a consonant + y, change the y to I before adding –ness. \nIf th',     'hlWords':["author's", "editor's", "gardener's", "neighbour's", "baker's", "farmer's", "singer's", "dancer's", "painter's", "driver's"]},
    {'id':'y2-t5-w5-l3','year':'Y2','term':'T5',     'week':5,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':'Mastery 12','lesson':'Lesson 2',     'focus':'Adding the suffix –ment, -ness & -ly',     'explanation':'The suffix ‘ment’ turns a verb into a noun. \nIt usually means: \n-The act of doing something\n-The result of an action\n-The state of something.\nFor example, the verb ‘improve’ changes to the noun ‘improvement’ and the verb ‘enjoy’ changes to the noun ‘enjoyment’.\nNo change is needed to the spelling of the root word.\nThe suffix ‘ness’ turns an adjective into a noun. It shows the stage, quality or condition of something.\nFor example, the adjective ‘kind’ turns into ‘kindness’ meaning the quality of being kind.\nIf the adjective ends in a consonant + y, change the y to I before adding –ness. \nIf th',     'hlWords':['action', 'invention', 'direction', 'selection', 'protection', 'question', 'option', 'section', 'fiction', 'station']},
    {'id':'y2-t5-w5-l4','year':'Y2','term':'T5',     'week':5,'weekLesson':4,     'sequence':'Mastery 13','lesson':'Lesson 1',     'focus':'contractions',     'explanation':'Apostrophes can be used for two reasons: contractions and possession.\nWhen we combine two words to form a contraction, the apostrophe is used to replace the missing letter(s).\nFor example, when we combine do + not, we omit the second letter ‘o’. \nTherefore, this is where the apostrophe is placed – don’t.\nWhen we use apostrophes for possession, we need to consider who the ‘owner’ is.\nThis is an example sentence:\nI borrowed the teacher’s book.\nIn this sentence, the book is ‘owned’ by the teacher. \nTherefore, we place the apostrophe in the word teacher’s.\nThe apostrophe is placed before the lett',     'hlWords':['location', 'completion', 'operation', 'decoration', 'celebration', 'education', 'donation', 'migration', 'population', 'nation']},
