    {'id':'y2-t6-w5-l1','year':'Y2','term':'T6',     'week':5,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':'Mastery 18','lesson':'Lesson 1',     'focus':'/or/ spelt ‘a’ or ‘ar’',     'explanation':'The /or/ phoneme is often spelt a before l or ll in common words. For example, in the words all, ball, call, fall, wall, small\nand tall. In many accents, this spelling can also be seen in words like walk and talk, where the sound changes over time.\nHowever, this spelling does not always make the /or/ sound. In other words with al, such as animal, metal, final and local, \nthe pronunciation is different and does not sound like /or/.\nThe /or/ phoneme has also be spelt ar following w or qu. For example, in the words warm and quarry. Words which use this \nspelling are usually war, time or number w',     'hlWords':['warm', 'warship', 'towards', 'quarter', 'ward', 'award', 'warmest', 'quartz', 'swarm', 'rewarded']},
    {'id':'y2-t6-w5-l2','year':'Y2','term':'T6',     'week':5,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':'Mastery 18','lesson':'Lesson 2',     'focus':'/or/ spelt ‘a’ or ‘ar’',     'explanation':'The /or/ phoneme is often spelt a before l or ll in common words. For example, in the words all, ball, call, fall, wall, small\nand tall. In many accents, this spelling can also be seen in words like walk and talk, where the sound changes over time.\nHowever, this spelling does not always make the /or/ sound. In other words with al, such as animal, metal, final and local, \nthe pronunciation is different and does not sound like /or/.\nThe /or/ phoneme has also be spelt ar following w or qu. For example, in the words warm and quarry. Words which use this \nspelling are usually war, time or number w',     'hlWords':['wardrobe', 'awards', 'talking', 'fallen', 'quarter', 'warm', 'wall', 'ball', 'swarm', 'always']},
    {'id':'y2-t6-w5-l3','year':'Y2','term':'T6',     'week':5,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':'Mastery 19','lesson':'Lesson 1',     'focus':'/zh/ spelt s',     'explanation':'The /zh/ phoneme is often spelt ‘s’ in the middle of words.\nThis often happens in longer words and between vowels. This is most commonly the case when the /zh/ sound comes before \nure, ion and ual.\nFor example, in the words measure, television and usual.',     'hlWords':['worse', 'worst', 'worthy', 'worship', 'word', 'worker', 'worth', 'world', 'worm', 'workbook']},
    {'id':'y2-t6-w5-l4','year':'Y2','term':'T6',     'week':5,'weekLesson':4,     'sequence':'Mastery 20','lesson':'Lesson 1',     'focus':'/er/ spelt or after w',     'explanation':'The /er/ phoneme is sometimes spelt ‘or’ after the letter ‘w’. \nThis can be seen in words such as word, work, worm, worth and world.',     'hlWords':['worst', 'bookworm', 'keyworker', 'worship', 'worthless', 'word', 'work', 'world', 'worm', 'worse']},
    {'id':'y2-t6-w5-l5','year':'Y2','term':'T6',     'week':5,'weekLesson':5,     'sequence':'Mastery 20','lesson':'Lesson 2',     'focus':'/er/ spelt or after w',     'explanation':'The /er/ phoneme is sometimes spelt ‘or’ after the letter ‘w’. \nThis can be seen in words such as word, work, worm, worth and world.',     'hlWords':['leisure', 'pleasure', 'composure', 'version', 'explosion', 'persuasion', 'casual', 'visually', 'unusual', 'closure']},
    {'id':'y3-t1-w1-l1','year':'Y3','term':'T1',     'week':1,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':'Revisit','lesson':'Lesson 1',     'focus':'words ending -le/-el/-al/-il',     'explanation':'The -le ending is the most commonly used of the endings in this unit.\nIt usually follows a consonant (other than those listed for the -el ending).\nThe -le ending is usually used when the last syllable of the word is unstressed.\nThe -el ending is often used after the letters m, n, r, s, v or w.\nExamples of these include camel, tunnel, squirrel, tinsel, travel and towel.\nThe -al ending is often applied when the word is an adjective.\nAn example of this would include magical (where the noun magic has formed the adjective magical).\nThere is no clear rule for the application of the -il ending (e.g.',     'hlWords':['apple', 'little', 'bottle', 'candle', 'simple', 'camel', 'towel', 'tunnel', 'squirrel', 'travel']},
    {'id':'y3-t1-w1-l2','year':'Y3','term':'T1',     'week':1,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':'Revisit','lesson':'Lesson 2',     'focus':'words ending -le/-el/-al/-il',     'explanation':'The -le ending is the most commonly used of the endings in this unit.\nIt usually follows a consonant (other than those listed for the -el ending).\nThe -le ending is usually used when the last syllable of the word is unstressed.\nThe -el ending is often used after the letters m, n, r, s, v or w.\nExamples of these include camel, tunnel, squirrel, tinsel, travel and towel.\nThe -al ending is often applied when the word is an adjective.\nAn example of this would include magical (where the noun magic has formed the adjective magical).\nThere is no clear rule for the application of the -il ending (e.g.',     'hlWords':['apple', 'candle', 'simple', 'camel', 'tunnel', 'travel', 'magical', 'personal', 'musical', 'natural']},
    {'id':'y3-t1-w1-l3','year':'Y3','term':'T1',     'week':1,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':'Revisit','lesson':'Lesson 3',     'focus':'words ending -le/-el/-al/-il',     'explanation':'The -le ending is the most commonly used of the endings in this unit.\nIt usually follows a consonant (other than those listed for the -el ending).\nThe -le ending is usually used when the last syllable of the word is unstressed.\nThe -el ending is often used after the letters m, n, r, s, v or w.\nExamples of these include camel, tunnel, squirrel, tinsel, travel and towel.\nThe -al ending is often applied when the word is an adjective.\nAn example of this would include magical (where the noun magic has formed the adjective magical).\nThere is no clear rule for the application of the -il ending (e.g.',     'hlWords':['handle', 'musical', 'channel', 'apple', 'little', 'camel', 'tunnel', 'magical', 'natural', 'personal']},
    {'id':'y3-t1-w2-l1','year':'Y3','term':'T1',     'week':2,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':'Revisit','lesson':'Lesson 4',     'focus':'adding -es after y',     'explanation':'These rules apply to nouns and verbs.\nWhen the word ends in a vowel + y, we simply add the letter ‘s’ to the end of the word.\nFor example, the word donkey becomes donkeys.\nWhen a word ends in a consonant + y, we must first change the letter ‘y’ to an ‘i’ before we add -es.\nFor example, the word carry becomes carries.\nWhen applying these rules to nouns, we are forming a plural noun (e.g. keys) from a singular noun (e.g. key).',     'hlWords':['plays', 'enjoys', 'valleys', 'holidays', 'journeys', 'babies', 'stories', 'armies', 'pennies', 'cities']},
    {'id':'y3-t1-w2-l2','year':'Y3','term':'T1',     'week':2,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':'Revisit','lesson':'Lesson 5',     'focus':'adding -es after y',     'explanation':'These rules apply to nouns and verbs.\nWhen the word ends in a vowel + y, we simply add the letter ‘s’ to the end of the word.\nFor example, the word donkey becomes donkeys.\nWhen a word ends in a consonant + y, we must first change the letter ‘y’ to an ‘i’ before we add -es.\nFor example, the word carry becomes carries.\nWhen applying these rules to nouns, we are forming a plural noun (e.g. keys) from a singular noun (e.g. key).',     'hlWords':['parties', 'stories', 'obeys', 'monkeys', 'surveys', 'jellies', 'armies', 'cities', 'mysteries', 'poppies']},
    {'id':'y3-t1-w2-l3','year':'Y3','term':'T1',     'week':2,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':'Revisit','lesson':'Lesson 6',     'focus':'adding -es after y',     'explanation':'These rules apply to nouns and verbs.\nWhen the word ends in a vowel + y, we simply add the letter ‘s’ to the end of the word.\nFor example, the word donkey becomes donkeys.\nWhen a word ends in a consonant + y, we must first change the letter ‘y’ to an ‘i’ before we add -es.\nFor example, the word carry becomes carries.\nWhen applying these rules to nouns, we are forming a plural noun (e.g. keys) from a singular noun (e.g. key).',     'hlWords':['families', 'diaries', 'delays', 'stories', 'babies', 'armies', 'mysteries', 'poppies', 'ladies', 'cries']},
    {'id':'y3-t1-w3-l1','year':'Y3','term':'T1',     'week':3,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':'Revisit','lesson':'Lesson 7',     'focus':'adding vowel suffixes',     'explanation':'When a word ends in a vowel + y, we simply add the vowel suffix.\nFor example, play becomes playing or played or player.\nWhen a word ends in a consonant + y, we simply add the -ing suffix.\nFor example, carry becomes carrying and reply becomes replying.\nThis rule changes when adding the suffixes -ed, -er and -est.\nFor these suffixes, when a word ends in a consonant + y, we change the y to i before we add the suffix.\nFor example, the word carry becomes carried and the word happy becomes happier.\nWhen a word ends in a consonant + e, we remove the e before we add a vowel suffix (-ed/-est/-er/-ing/',     'hlWords':['copying', 'crying', 'replying', 'hurrying', 'drying', 'copied', 'cried', 'replied', 'hurried', 'supplied']},
    {'id':'y3-t1-w3-l2','year':'Y3','term':'T1',     'week':3,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':'Revisit','lesson':'Lesson 8',     'focus':'adding vowel suffixes',     'explanation':'When a word ends in a vowel + y, we simply add the vowel suffix.\nFor example, play becomes playing or played or player.\nWhen a word ends in a consonant + y, we simply add the -ing suffix.\nFor example, carry becomes carrying and reply becomes replying.\nThis rule changes when adding the suffixes -ed, -er and -est.\nFor these suffixes, when a word ends in a consonant + y, we change the y to i before we add the suffix.\nFor example, the word carry becomes carried and the word happy becomes happier.\nWhen a word ends in a consonant + e, we remove the e before we add a vowel suffix (-ed/-est/-er/-ing/',     'hlWords':['happier', 'angrier', 'busier', 'dirtier', 'lazier', 'happiest', 'angriest', 'busiest', 'drier', 'prettiest']},
    {'id':'y3-t1-w3-l3','year':'Y3','term':'T1',     'week':3,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':'Revisit','lesson':'Lesson 9',     'focus':'adding vowel suffixes',     'explanation':'When a word ends in a vowel + y, we simply add the vowel suffix.\nFor example, play becomes playing or played or player.\nWhen a word ends in a consonant + y, we simply add the -ing suffix.\nFor example, carry becomes carrying and reply becomes replying.\nThis rule changes when adding the suffixes -ed, -er and -est.\nFor these suffixes, when a word ends in a consonant + y, we change the y to i before we add the suffix.\nFor example, the word carry becomes carried and the word happy becomes happier.\nWhen a word ends in a consonant + e, we remove the e before we add a vowel suffix (-ed/-est/-er/-ing/',     'hlWords':['moving', 'baking', 'writing', 'dancing', 'driving', 'mover', 'baker', 'writer', 'dancer', 'driver']},
    {'id':'y3-t1-w4-l1','year':'Y3','term':'T1',     'week':4,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':'Revisit','lesson':'Lesson 10',     'focus':'doubling consonants in one-syllable words',     'explanation':'This rule is complex because it contains several considerations and skills:\n1.\nThe number of syllables in the word\n2.\nThe final two letters of the word\n3.\nKnowledge of vowels and consonants\n4.\nKnowledge of vowel suffixes\nFor the purposes of vowel suffix rules, the letter ‘y’ is considered a vowel when applied as a suffix.\nWhen a word with one syllable ends in a single short vowel + consonant, we double the consonant before \nadding the vowel suffix (-ed/-ing/-er/-est/-y).\nFor example, the word jump ends in consonant + consonant.\nTherefore, we do not double the consonant (e.g. jumped or jumping',     'hlWords':['patted', 'hummed', 'dropped', 'patting', 'humming', 'dropping', 'running', 'sitting', 'getting', 'bigger']},
    {'id':'y3-t1-w4-l2','year':'Y3','term':'T1',     'week':4,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':'Revisit','lesson':'Lesson 11',     'focus':'doubling consonants in one-syllable words',     'explanation':'This rule is complex because it contains several considerations and skills:\n1.\nThe number of syllables in the word\n2.\nThe final two letters of the word\n3.\nKnowledge of vowels and consonants\n4.\nKnowledge of vowel suffixes\nFor the purposes of vowel suffix rules, the letter ‘y’ is considered a vowel when applied as a suffix.\nWhen a word with one syllable ends in a single short vowel + consonant, we double the consonant before \nadding the vowel suffix (-ed/-ing/-er/-est/-y).\nFor example, the word jump ends in consonant + consonant.\nTherefore, we do not double the consonant (e.g. jumped or jumping',     'hlWords':['patted', 'hummed', 'dropped', 'patting', 'humming', 'dropping', 'running', 'sitting', 'hopped', 'tapping']},
    {'id':'y3-t1-w4-l3','year':'Y3','term':'T1',     'week':4,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':'Revisit','lesson':'Lesson 12',     'focus':'doubling consonants in one-syllable words',     'explanation':'This rule is complex because it contains several considerations and skills:\n1.\nThe number of syllables in the word\n2.\nThe final two letters of the word\n3.\nKnowledge of vowels and consonants\n4.\nKnowledge of vowel suffixes\nFor the purposes of vowel suffix rules, the letter ‘y’ is considered a vowel when applied as a suffix.\nWhen a word with one syllable ends in a single short vowel + consonant, we double the consonant before \nadding the vowel suffix (-ed/-ing/-er/-est/-y).\nFor example, the word jump ends in consonant + consonant.\nTherefore, we do not double the consonant (e.g. jumped or jumping',     'hlWords':['hopped', 'hopping', 'stopped', 'stopping', 'clapped', 'clapping', 'grabbed', 'grabbing', 'tipped', 'tipping']},
    {'id':'y3-t1-w5-l1','year':'Y3','term':'T1',     'week':5,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':'Revisit','lesson':'Lesson 13',     'focus':'apostrophes',     'explanation':'Apostrophes can be used for two reasons: contractions and possession.\nWhen we combine two words to form a contraction, the apostrophe is used to replace the missing letter(s).\nFor example, when we combine do + not, we omit the second letter ‘o’. \nTherefore, this is where the apostrophe is placed – don’t.\nWhen we use apostrophes for possession, we need to consider who the ‘owner’ is.\nThis is an example sentence:\nI borrowed the teacher’s book.\nIn this sentence, the book is ‘owned’ by the teacher. \nTherefore, we place the apostrophe in the word teacher’s.\nThe apostrophe is placed before the lett',     'hlWords':["don't", "didn't", "wouldn't", "we're", "you're", "they're", "isn't", "can't", "haven't", "I'm"]},
    {'id':'y3-t1-w5-l2','year':'Y3','term':'T1',     'week':5,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':'Revisit','lesson':'Lesson 14',     'focus':'apostrophes',     'explanation':'Apostrophes can be used for two reasons: contractions and possession.\nWhen we combine two words to form a contraction, the apostrophe is used to replace the missing letter(s).\nFor example, when we combine do + not, we omit the second letter ‘o’. \nTherefore, this is where the apostrophe is placed – don’t.\nWhen we use apostrophes for possession, we need to consider who the ‘owner’ is.\nThis is an example sentence:\nI borrowed the teacher’s book.\nIn this sentence, the book is ‘owned’ by the teacher. \nTherefore, we place the apostrophe in the word teacher’s.\nThe apostrophe is placed before the lett',     'hlWords':["teacher's", "dog's", "friend's", "we're", "you've", "doesn't", "boy's", "cat's", "girl's", "mum's"]},
    {'id':'y3-t1-w5-l3','year':'Y3','term':'T1',     'week':5,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':'Revisit','lesson':'Lesson 15',     'focus':'apostrophes',     'explanation':'Apostrophes can be used for two reasons: contractions and possession.\nWhen we combine two words to form a contraction, the apostrophe is used to replace the missing letter(s).\nFor example, when we combine do + not, we omit the second letter ‘o’. \nTherefore, this is where the apostrophe is placed – don’t.\nWhen we use apostrophes for possession, we need to consider who the ‘owner’ is.\nThis is an example sentence:\nI borrowed the teacher’s book.\nIn this sentence, the book is ‘owned’ by the teacher. \nTherefore, we place the apostrophe in the word teacher’s.\nThe apostrophe is placed before the lett',     'hlWords':["couldn't", "I've", "you're", "door's", "child's", "didn't", "isn't", "haven't", "boy's", "we're"]},
    {'id':'y3-t2-w1-l1','year':'Y3','term':'T2',     'week':1,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':'Sequence 1','lesson':'Lesson 1',     'focus':'doubling consonants',     'explanation':'When a word with more than one syllable ends in a single short vowel letter + consonant, and the last syllable is stressed\nwe double the consonant before adding the vowel suffix.\n(A syllable being stressed means that it is the most emphasised syllable – it is louder or clearer than the others when spoken \naloud.)\nThe word ‘open’ ends in a single vowel (e) + single consonant (n).\nIn the word o-pen, it is the first syllable (making the long o sound) that is stressed. \nTherefore, when we add a vowel suffix, we do not double the final consonant.\nFor example, we simply add the -ed suffix to get op',     'hlWords':['jump', 'bank', 'drift', 'stack', 'blend', 'jumped', 'banking', 'drifted', 'stacked', 'blending']},
