    {'id':'y3-t3-w3-l1','year':'Y3','term':'T3',     'week':3,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':'Mastery 1','lesson':'Lesson 1',     'focus':'doubling consonants',     'explanation':'When a word with more than one syllable ends in a single short vowel letter + consonant, and the last syllable \nis stressed we double the consonant before adding the vowel suffix.\n(A syllable being stressed means that it is the most emphasised syllable – it is louder or clearer than the others \nwhen spoken aloud.)\nThe word ‘open’ ends in a single vowel (e) + single consonant (n).\nIn the word o-pen, it is the first syllable (making the long o sound) that is stressed. \nTherefore, when we add a vowel suffix, we do not double the final consonant.\nFor example, we simply add the -ed suffix to get o',     'hlWords':['joyous', 'poisonous', 'venomous', 'famous', 'nervous', 'continuous', 'gorgeous', 'courageous', 'outrageous', 'hazardous']},
    {'id':'y3-t3-w3-l2','year':'Y3','term':'T3',     'week':3,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':'Mastery 1','lesson':'Lesson 2',     'focus':'doubling consonants',     'explanation':'When a word with more than one syllable ends in a single short vowel letter + consonant, and the last syllable \nis stressed we double the consonant before adding the vowel suffix.\n(A syllable being stressed means that it is the most emphasised syllable – it is louder or clearer than the others \nwhen spoken aloud.)\nThe word ‘open’ ends in a single vowel (e) + single consonant (n).\nIn the word o-pen, it is the first syllable (making the long o sound) that is stressed. \nTherefore, when we add a vowel suffix, we do not double the final consonant.\nFor example, we simply add the -ed suffix to get o',     'hlWords':['horrendous', 'jealous', 'anonymous', 'vigorous', 'glamorous', 'vaporous', 'envious', 'studious', 'mysterious', 'various']},
