    {'id':'y3-t4-w3-l1','year':'Y3','term':'T4',     'week':3,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':'Sequence 6','lesson':'Lesson 1',     'focus':'alternative long a sounds',     'explanation':'The long a sound has various representations.\nIn this sequence, children are introduced to the following graphemes – ei / eigh / ey.\nThe ei grapheme is often found in the middle of a word.\nExamples include rein, beige and veil.\nThe ey grapheme is often found at the end of a word.\nExamples include grey, obey and survey.\nThe eigh grapheme can be found in different positions within words.\nThe most common roots that use this grapheme include eight, weigh and neigh.\nThese roots form many other words containing the same grapheme (e.g. eighteen and neighbour).',     'hlWords':['acorn', 'snake', 'rain', 'today', 'vein', 'eight', 'sleigh', 'grey', 'they', 'neighbour']},
    {'id':'y3-t4-w3-l2','year':'Y3','term':'T4',     'week':3,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':'Sequence 6','lesson':'Lesson 2',     'focus':'alternative long a sounds',     'explanation':'The long a sound has various representations.\nIn this sequence, children are introduced to the following graphemes – ei / eigh / ey.\nThe ei grapheme is often found in the middle of a word.\nExamples include rein, beige and veil.\nThe ey grapheme is often found at the end of a word.\nExamples include grey, obey and survey.\nThe eigh grapheme can be found in different positions within words.\nThe most common roots that use this grapheme include eight, weigh and neigh.\nThese roots form many other words containing the same grapheme (e.g. eighteen and neighbour).',     'hlWords':['they', 'prey', 'grey', 'obey', 'survey', 'vein', 'beige', 'eight', 'sleigh', 'weight']},
    {'id':'y3-t4-w3-l3','year':'Y3','term':'T4',     'week':3,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':'Sequence 6','lesson':'Lesson 3',     'focus':'alternative long a sounds',     'explanation':'The long a sound has various representations.\nIn this sequence, children are introduced to the following graphemes – ei / eigh / ey.\nThe ei grapheme is often found in the middle of a word.\nExamples include rein, beige and veil.\nThe ey grapheme is often found at the end of a word.\nExamples include grey, obey and survey.\nThe eigh grapheme can be found in different positions within words.\nThe most common roots that use this grapheme include eight, weigh and neigh.\nThese roots form many other words containing the same grapheme (e.g. eighteen and neighbour).',     'hlWords':['eighteen', 'convey', 'reign', 'they', 'grey', 'obey', 'survey', 'vein', 'eight', 'sleigh']},
    {'id':'y3-t4-w4-l1','year':'Y3','term':'T4',     'week':4,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':'Sequence 7','lesson':'Lesson 1',     'focus':'homophones',     'explanation':'Homophones are words that sound the same but have different spellings and meanings.\nyour / you’re\nThe word your is possessive. It indicates that something belongs to you.\nPlease hand in your book.\nThe word you’re is a contraction of you are. \nI know that you’re trying hard.\nthere / their / they’re\nThe word there refers to a place or can be used to point out something.\nPut your shoes over there.\nThe word their shows possession. It indicates that someone owns something.\nWe visited their house yesterday.\nThe word they’re is a contraction of they are.\nThey told me they’re going to be late.\nto / t',     'hlWords':["you're", 'your', 'there', 'their', "they're", 'to', 'too', 'two', 'here', 'hear']},
