    {'id':'y3-t4-w5-l1','year':'Y3','term':'T4',     'week':5,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':'Sequence 7','lesson':'Lesson 4',     'focus':'homophones',     'explanation':'Homophones are words that sound the same but have different spellings and meanings.\nhere / hear\nThe word here relates to a place or position.\nWait here until they arrive.\nThe word hear relates to sound or listening.\nCan you hear the music?\nled / lead\nThe word led is a past tense verb. It refers to guiding someone.\nThe teacher led the class outside.\nThe word lead is a type of metal (often found in pencils).\nThat pencil contains lead.',     'hlWords':['here', 'hear', 'there', 'their', 'to', 'too', "you're", 'your', 'male', 'mail']},
    {'id':'y3-t4-w5-l2','year':'Y3','term':'T4',     'week':5,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':'Sequence 7','lesson':'Lesson 5',     'focus':'homophones',     'explanation':'Homophones are words that sound the same but have different spellings and meanings.\nmale / mail\nThe word male relates to a person’s gender – it refers to a boy or man.\nThe male lion has a large mane.\nThe word mail relates to letters or packages sent by post.\nI received a letter in the mail.\nmeet / meat\nThe word meet is a verb. It means to come together with someone.\nI will meet my friend at school.\nThe word meat is a noun. It refers to the food product derived from an animal.\nWe had meat and vegetables for dinner.',     'hlWords':['male', 'mail', 'here', 'hear', 'there', 'their', 'to', 'too', 'great', 'grate']},
    {'id':'y3-t4-w5-l3','year':'Y3','term':'T4',     'week':5,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':'Sequence 7','lesson':'Lesson 6',     'focus':'homophones',     'explanation':'Homophones are words that sound the same but have different spellings and meanings.\ngreat / grate\nThe word great refers to something that is good or big.\nShe had a great idea. We stood in front of a great mountain.\nThe word grate refers to shredding a food or something annoying.\nI will grate the cheese. The noise started to grate on me.\nseen / scene\nThe word seen is a past tense verb. It means to look at something with your eyes.\nI have seen dolphins before.\nThe word scene is a noun. It refers to a place or part of a story or play.\nThe final scene of the film was my favourite.',     'hlWords':['great', 'grate', 'male', 'mail', 'here', 'hear', 'there', 'their', 'to', 'too']},
