    {'id':'y3-t5-w4-l1','year':'Y3','term':'T5',     'week':4,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':'Sequence 9','lesson':'Lesson 1',     'focus':'LKS2 Word List',     'explanation':'This lesson focuses on the following words from the LKS2 Statutory Word List:\neight, eighth, weight, height, straight\nThe focus of this lesson is on words containing the eigh and aigh quadgraphs.\nA quadgraph is a grapheme comprised of four letters.\nIn the word eight, the eigh grapheme produces the long a sound.\nIn the word eighth, the eigh grapheme produces the long a sound.\nIn the word weight, the eigh grapheme produces the long a sound.\nIn the word height, the eigh grapheme produces the long i sound.\nIn the word straight, the aigh grapheme produces the long a sound.',     'hlWords':['eighth', 'eight', 'weight', 'straight', 'height', 'eighteen', 'neighbour', 'sleigh', 'freight', 'eighty']},
    {'id':'y3-t5-w4-l2','year':'Y3','term':'T5',     'week':4,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':'Sequence 9','lesson':'Lesson 2',     'focus':'LKS2 Word List',     'explanation':'This lesson focuses on the following words from the LKS2 Statutory Word List:\nthough, although, enough, through, thought\nThe focus of this lesson is on words containing the ough quadgraph.\nA quadgraph is a grapheme comprised of four letters.\nIn the word though, the ough grapheme produces the long o (oa) sound.\nIn the word although, the ough grapheme produces the long o (oa) sound.\nIn the word enough, the ough grapheme produces the uff sound.\nIn the word through, the ough grapheme produces the oo sound.\nIn the word thought, the ough grapheme produces the aw sound.',     'hlWords':['eight', 'eighth', 'weight', 'height', 'weigh', 'eighteen', 'freight', 'sleigh', 'neigh', 'neighbour']},
    {'id':'y3-t5-w4-l3','year':'Y3','term':'T5',     'week':4,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':'Sequence 9','lesson':'Lesson 3',     'focus':'LKS2 Word List',     'explanation':'This lesson focuses on the following words from the LKS2 Statutory Word List:\ncaught, length, strength, strange\nThe word caught features an unusual quadgraph.\nThe augh quadgraph is used to represent the aw sound.\nc-augh-t\nThe words length and strength feature an unusual consonant cluster (ngth).\nIt may be helpful to separate the ng and th in these words.\nl-eng-th\nstr-eng-th\nThe word strange features the long a sound.\nHowever, it does not contain a split digraph as there are two letters between the a and e.\nIn addition, the j sound is produced by the letter g.',     'hlWords':['though', 'although', 'enough', 'through', 'thought', 'bought', 'brought', 'ought', 'rough', 'tough']},
    {'id':'y3-t5-w5-l1','year':'Y3','term':'T5',     'week':5,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':'Sequence 9','lesson':'Lesson 4',     'focus':'LKS2 Word List',     'explanation':'This lesson focuses on the following words from the LKS2 Statutory Word List:\nbreath / breathe / woman / women\nbreath vs breathe\nThe word breath is a noun. It is spelled without an e on the end.\nIt refers to the air that you take in (inhale) and let out (exhale).\nThe word breathe is a verb. It is spelled with an e on the end.\nIt refers to the action of taking in air (inhaling) and letting out air (exhaling).\nwoman vs women\nThe word woman is singular. It is spelled with an a (like man).\nIt refers to one female adult.\nThe word women is a plural. It is spelled with an e (like men).\nIt refers to',     'hlWords':['caught', 'length', 'strength', 'strange', 'money', 'journey', 'monkey', 'chimney', 'volley', 'jockey']},
    {'id':'y3-t5-w5-l2','year':'Y3','term':'T5',     'week':5,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':'Sequence 9','lesson':'Lesson 5',     'focus':'LKS2 Word List',     'explanation':'This lesson focuses on the following words from the LKS2 Statutory Word List:\ncomplete / describe / extreme / separate\nThese words all end with a split digraph.\ncomplete – long e \ndescribe – long i\nextreme – long e\nseparate – long a\nIn addition, the word describe begins with the unusual spelling of des (sounding like dis).\nThe word separate contains the er sound spelled ar. \n(A helpful mnemonic is, “There is a rat in separate.)',     'hlWords':['breath', 'breathe', 'woman', 'women', 'build', 'busy', 'calendar', 'century', 'certain', 'circle']},
    {'id':'y3-t5-w5-l3','year':'Y3','term':'T5',     'week':5,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':'Sequence 9','lesson':'Lesson 6',     'focus':'LKS2 Word List',     'explanation':'This lesson focuses on the following words from the LKS2 Statutory Word List:\nimagine / medicine / notice / promise\nThese words all look like they end with a split digraph. \nHowever, the e is silent and the other vowel produces the short i sound.\nThe word imagine contains the j sound spelled g.\nThe word medicine contains the s sound spelled c.\nThe word notice contains the s sound spelled c.\nThe word promise contains the s sound.\nHowever, although it sounds like it ends with miss, there is only one s.',     'hlWords':['describe', 'separate', 'complete', 'extreme', 'decide', 'favourite', 'forward', 'fruit', 'grammar', 'guard']},
    {'id':'y3-t6-w1-l1','year':'Y3','term':'T6',     'week':1,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':'Sequence 9','lesson':'Lesson 7',     'focus':'LKS2 Word List',     'explanation':'This lesson focuses on the following words from the LKS2 Statutory Word List:\nearly / earth / learn / heart / guide / guard\nFour of these words contain the ear grapheme.\nIn the words early, earth and learn, the ear grapheme represents the er sound.\nIn the word heart, the ear grapheme represents the ar sound.\nThe final two words (guide / guard) contain a silent u after the letter g at the beginning of the word.',     'hlWords':['version', 'confusion', 'revision', 'fusion', 'television', 'inclusion', 'division', 'exclusion', 'corrosion', 'invasion']},
    {'id':'y3-t6-w1-l2','year':'Y3','term':'T6',     'week':1,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':'Sequence 9','lesson':'Lesson 8',     'focus':'LKS2 Word List',     'explanation':'This lesson focuses on the following words from the LKS2 Statutory Word List:\nbuild / answer / island / often / interest / history / natural / knowledge\nThe focus of this lesson in on identifying the silent letter within each word.\nbuild (u)\nanswer (w)\nisland (s)\noften (t)\ninterest (e)\nhistory (o) – This word contains the word ‘story’.\nnatural (u)\nknowledge (k/w) – This word contains two silent letters. The root word is ‘know’.',     'hlWords':['corrosion', 'exclusion', 'precision', 'diffusion', 'decision', 'version', 'confusion', 'revision', 'inclusion', 'division']},
    {'id':'y3-t6-w1-l3','year':'Y3','term':'T6',     'week':1,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':'Sequence 9','lesson':'Lesson 9',     'focus':'LKS2 Word List',     'explanation':'This lesson focuses on the following words from the LKS2 Statutory Word List:\nbelieve / business / favourite / February / library / forward\nThe focus of this lesson in on identifying the challenging parts of each word.\nbelieve – The long e sound is represented by the ie grapheme. The ‘be’ start often sounds like ‘bi’ when spoken.\nbusiness – The root word is busy. We change the y to i before applying -ness.\nfavourite – The word favourite contains the word ‘our’. It ends with a silent e.\nFebruary – The letter r (after b) is often missed. The word needs capitalising because it is a proper noun.',     'hlWords':['conclusion', 'revision', 'confusion', 'division', 'invasion', 'collision', 'version', 'television', 'exclusion', 'inclusion']},
    {'id':'y3-t6-w2-l1','year':'Y3','term':'T6',     'week':2,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':'Mastery 4','lesson':'Lesson 1',     'focus':'words ending -sion',     'explanation':'The -sion ending is applied to verbs to form nouns.\nThe -sion ending sounds like zh-un.\nWhen a verb ends in se, we can remove se and replace it with sion.\nFor example, the verb confuse can be used to form the noun confusion.\nWhen a verb ends in de, we can remove de and replace it with sion.\nFor example, the verb decide can be used to form the noun decision.',     'hlWords':['myth', 'gym', 'hymn', 'synonym', 'antonym', 'system', 'rhythm', 'mystery', 'syllable', 'crystal']},
    {'id':'y3-t6-w2-l2','year':'Y3','term':'T6',     'week':2,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':'Mastery 4','lesson':'Lesson 2',     'focus':'words ending -sion',     'explanation':'The -sion ending is applied to verbs to form nouns.\nThe -sion ending sounds like zh-un.\nWhen a verb ends in se, we can remove se and replace it with sion.\nFor example, the verb confuse can be used to form the noun confusion.\nWhen a verb ends in de, we can remove de and replace it with sion.\nFor example, the verb decide can be used to form the noun decision.',     'hlWords':['myth', 'mystical', 'syrup', 'sympathy', 'symmetry', 'antonym', 'symbol', 'typical', 'gym', 'hymn']},
    {'id':'y3-t6-w2-l3','year':'Y3','term':'T6',     'week':2,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':'Mastery 4','lesson':'Lesson 3',     'focus':'words ending -sion',     'explanation':'The -sion ending is applied to verbs to form nouns.\nThe -sion ending sounds like zh-un.\nWhen a verb ends in se, we can remove se and replace it with sion.\nFor example, the verb confuse can be used to form the noun confusion.\nWhen a verb ends in de, we can remove de and replace it with sion.\nFor example, the verb decide can be used to form the noun decision.',     'hlWords':['rhythm', 'cylinder', 'crystal', 'synonym', 'lyrics', 'pyramid', 'gym', 'myth', 'system', 'typical']},
    {'id':'y3-t6-w3-l1','year':'Y3','term':'T6',     'week':3,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':'Mastery 5','lesson':'Lesson 1',     'focus':'i sound spelled y',     'explanation':'Within some words, the short i sound is represented by the letter y.\n(This is not the case at the end of words.)\nThere is no spelling rule for words containing the short i sound spelled y.\nInstead, these words simply have to be learned.\nHowever, there are some useful patterns.\nFor example, the short i sound spelled y often appears after the letter s at the beginning of a word.\nIn addition, it often precedes or follows the letter m.',     'hlWords':['beige', 'vein', 'reindeer', 'eight', 'neigh', 'weight', 'they', 'obey', 'survey', 'grey']},
