    {'id':'y3-t6-w3-l3','year':'Y3','term':'T6',     'week':3,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':'Mastery 5','lesson':'Lesson 3',     'focus':'i sound spelled y',     'explanation':'Within some words, the short i sound is represented by the letter y.\n(This is not the case at the end of words.)\nThere is no spelling rule for words containing the short i sound spelled y.\nInstead, these words simply have to be learned.\nHowever, there are some useful patterns.\nFor example, the short i sound spelled y often appears after the letter s at the beginning of a word.\nIn addition, it often precedes or follows the letter m.',     'hlWords':['eighty', 'veins', 'grey', 'survey', 'neighbour', 'weight', 'veil', 'eight', 'neigh', 'obey']},
    {'id':'y3-t6-w4-l1','year':'Y3','term':'T6',     'week':4,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':'Mastery 6','lesson':'Lesson 1',     'focus':'alternative long a sounds',     'explanation':'The long a sound has various representations.\nIn this sequence, children are introduced to the following graphemes – ei / eigh / ey.\nThe ei grapheme is often found in the middle of a word.\nExamples include rein, beige and veil.\nThe ey grapheme is often found at the end of a word.\nExamples include grey, obey and survey.\nThe eigh grapheme can be found in different positions within words.\nThe most common roots that use this grapheme include eight, weigh and neigh.\nThese roots form many other words containing the same grapheme (e.g. eighteen and neighbour).',     'hlWords':['election', 'adoption', 'selection', 'creation', 'pollution', 'animation', 'extension', 'expansion', 'decision', 'tension']},
    {'id':'y3-t6-w4-l2','year':'Y3','term':'T6',     'week':4,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':'Mastery 6','lesson':'Lesson 2',     'focus':'alternative long a sounds',     'explanation':'The long a sound has various representations.\nIn this sequence, children are introduced to the following graphemes – ei / eigh / ey.\nThe ei grapheme is often found in the middle of a word.\nExamples include rein, beige and veil.\nThe ey grapheme is often found at the end of a word.\nExamples include grey, obey and survey.\nThe eigh grapheme can be found in different positions within words.\nThe most common roots that use this grapheme include eight, weigh and neigh.\nThese roots form many other words containing the same grapheme (e.g. eighteen and neighbour).',     'hlWords':['decision', 'pollution', 'donation', 'direction', 'extension', 'tension', 'decide', 'pollute', 'donate', 'direct']},
    {'id':'y3-t6-w4-l3','year':'Y3','term':'T6',     'week':4,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':'Mastery 6','lesson':'Lesson 3',     'focus':'alternative long a sounds',     'explanation':'The long a sound has various representations.\nIn this sequence, children are introduced to the following graphemes – ei / eigh / ey.\nThe ei grapheme is often found in the middle of a word.\nExamples include rein, beige and veil.\nThe ey grapheme is often found at the end of a word.\nExamples include grey, obey and survey.\nThe eigh grapheme can be found in different positions within words.\nThe most common roots that use this grapheme include eight, weigh and neigh.\nThese roots form many other words containing the same grapheme (e.g. eighteen and neighbour).',     'hlWords':['expansion', 'creation', 'clinician', 'permission', 'invention', 'obsession', 'decision', 'physician', 'donation', 'election']},
    {'id':'y3-t6-w5-l1','year':'Y3','term':'T6',     'week':5,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':'Mastery 7','lesson':'Lesson 1',     'focus':'tion/sion/ssion/cian',     'explanation':'These suffixes are pronounced like ‘shun’.\nThe -tion suffix is often used if the root word ends in t or te.\nFor example, the word complete becomes completion.\nThe -sion suffix is often used if the root word ends in d, de or se.\nFor example, the word decide becomes decision.\nThe -ssion suffix is often used if the root word ends in ss or mit.\nFor example, the word admit becomes admission.\nThe -cian suffix is often used if the root word ends in c or cs. \nFor example, the word electric becomes electrician.\nIt is mostly used to indicate a profession – e.g. magician.\nIt is important to note that th',     'hlWords':['monkey', 'kidney', 'jockey', 'trolley', 'valley', 'journey', 'medicine', 'notice', 'promise', 'imagine']},
    {'id':'y3-t6-w5-l2','year':'Y3','term':'T6',     'week':5,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':'Mastery 7','lesson':'Lesson 2',     'focus':'tion/sion/ssion/cian',     'explanation':'These suffixes are pronounced like ‘shun’.\nThe -tion suffix is often used if the root word ends in t or te.\nFor example, the word complete becomes completion.\nThe -sion suffix is often used if the root word ends in d, de or se.\nFor example, the word decide becomes decision.\nThe -ssion suffix is often used if the root word ends in ss or mit.\nFor example, the word admit becomes admission.\nThe -cian suffix is often used if the root word ends in c or cs. \nFor example, the word electric becomes electrician.\nIt is mostly used to indicate a profession – e.g. magician.\nIt is important to note that th',     'hlWords':['early', 'earth', 'guide', 'heart', 'guard', 'learn', 'answer', 'often', 'island', 'build']},
    {'id':'y3-t6-w5-l3','year':'Y3','term':'T6',     'week':5,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':'Mastery 7','lesson':'Lesson 3',     'focus':'tion/sion/ssion/cian',     'explanation':'These suffixes are pronounced like ‘shun’.\nThe -tion suffix is often used if the root word ends in t or te.\nFor example, the word complete becomes completion.\nThe -sion suffix is often used if the root word ends in d, de or se.\nFor example, the word decide becomes decision.\nThe -ssion suffix is often used if the root word ends in ss or mit.\nFor example, the word admit becomes admission.\nThe -cian suffix is often used if the root word ends in c or cs. \nFor example, the word electric becomes electrician.\nIt is mostly used to indicate a profession – e.g. magician.\nIt is important to note that th',     'hlWords':['decision', 'musician', 'connection', 'population', 'possession', 'physician', 'answer', 'often', 'island', 'build']},
    {'id':'y4-t1-w1-l1','year':'Y4','term':'T1',     'week':1,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':'Revisit','lesson':'Lesson 1',     'focus':'doubling consonants',     'explanation':'When a word with more than one syllable ends in a single short vowel letter + consonant, and the last syllable \nis stressed we double the consonant before adding the vowel suffix.\n(A syllable being stressed means that it is the most emphasised syllable – it is louder or clearer than the others \nwhen spoken aloud.)\nThe word ‘open’ ends in a single vowel (e) + single consonant (n).\nIn the word o-pen, it is the first syllable (making the long o sound) that is stressed. \nTherefore, when we add a vowel suffix, we do not double the final consonant.\nFor example, we simply add the -ed suffix to get o',     'hlWords':['referred', 'preferring', 'committed', 'beginner', 'forgetting', 'inferred', 'referral', 'covering', 'listening', 'gardener']},
    {'id':'y4-t1-w1-l2','year':'Y4','term':'T1',     'week':1,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':'Revisit','lesson':'Lesson 2',     'focus':'doubling consonants',     'explanation':'When a word with more than one syllable ends in a single short vowel letter + consonant, and the last syllable \nis stressed we double the consonant before adding the vowel suffix.\n(A syllable being stressed means that it is the most emphasised syllable – it is louder or clearer than the others \nwhen spoken aloud.)\nThe word ‘open’ ends in a single vowel (e) + single consonant (n).\nIn the word o-pen, it is the first syllable (making the long o sound) that is stressed. \nTherefore, when we add a vowel suffix, we do not double the final consonant.\nFor example, we simply add the -ed suffix to get o',     'hlWords':['transmitting', 'committed', 'inferring', 'regretted', 'occurrence', 'equipped', 'transferred', 'preferred', 'focusing', 'happening']},
    {'id':'y4-t1-w1-l3','year':'Y4','term':'T1',     'week':1,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':'Revisit','lesson':'Lesson 3',     'focus':'doubling consonants',     'explanation':'When a word with more than one syllable ends in a single short vowel letter + consonant, and the last syllable \nis stressed we double the consonant before adding the vowel suffix.\n(A syllable being stressed means that it is the most emphasised syllable – it is louder or clearer than the others \nwhen spoken aloud.)\nThe word ‘open’ ends in a single vowel (e) + single consonant (n).\nIn the word o-pen, it is the first syllable (making the long o sound) that is stressed. \nTherefore, when we add a vowel suffix, we do not double the final consonant.\nFor example, we simply add the -ed suffix to get o',     'hlWords':['preferred', 'preference', 'benefitting', 'occurred', 'admitting', 'controlled', 'transferring', 'forgotten', 'beginning', 'equipped']},
    {'id':'y4-t1-w2-l1','year':'Y4','term':'T1',     'week':2,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':'Revisit','lesson':'Lesson 4',     'focus':'adding the -ly suffix',     'explanation':'For most root words, we simply add the -ly suffix (because it begins with a consonant).\nHowever, there are some exceptions to this where other rules apply.\nIf the root word ends in y, change y to i before adding -ly.\nFor example, the word happy becomes happily.\nIf the root word ends in -le, change -le to -ly.\nFor example, the word gentle becomes gently.\nIf the root word ends in -ic, use the -ally suffix (instead of -ly).\nFor example, the word magic becomes magically.',     'hlWords':['magically', 'steadily', 'easily', 'grumpily', 'sensibly', 'simply', 'angrily', 'logically', 'terribly', 'basically']},
    {'id':'y4-t1-w2-l2','year':'Y4','term':'T1',     'week':2,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':'Revisit','lesson':'Lesson 5',     'focus':'adding the -ly suffix',     'explanation':'For most root words, we simply add the -ly suffix (because it begins with a consonant).\nHowever, there are some exceptions to this where other rules apply.\nIf the root word ends in y, change y to i before adding -ly.\nFor example, the word happy becomes happily.\nIf the root word ends in -le, change -le to -ly.\nFor example, the word gentle becomes gently.\nIf the root word ends in -ic, use the -ally suffix (instead of -ly).\nFor example, the word magic becomes magically.',     'hlWords':['quickly', 'sleepily', 'luckily', 'tragically', 'gently', 'bravely', 'musically', 'clearly', 'greedily', 'honestly']},
    {'id':'y4-t1-w2-l3','year':'Y4','term':'T1',     'week':2,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':'Revisit','lesson':'Lesson 6',     'focus':'adding the -ous suffix',     'explanation':'When there is an obvious root word, the usual rules apply for adding a vowel suffix.\nFor most words, the -ous suffix is simply added.\nFor example, the word danger becomes dangerous.\nWhen the root word ends in y, we change y to i before adding -ous.\nFor example, the word vary becomes various.\nWhen the root word ends in e, we remove the e before adding -ous.\nFor example, the word fame becomes famous.\nIn addition, if the root word ends in -our, we change it to -or before adding -ous.\nFor example, the word humour becomes humorous.\nThe final ‘e’ of the root word must be kept if the /dʒ/ sound of ‘',     'hlWords':['dangerous', 'furious', 'nervous', 'outrageous', 'humorous', 'glorious', 'adventurous', 'poisonous', 'courageous', 'mysterious']},
    {'id':'y4-t1-w3-l1','year':'Y4','term':'T1',     'week':3,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':'Revisit','lesson':'Lesson 7',     'focus':'the suffixes -tion/-sion/-ssion/-cian',     'explanation':'These suffixes are pronounced like ‘shun’.\nThe -tion suffix is often used if the root word ends in t or te.\nFor example, the word complete becomes completion.\nThe -sion suffix is often used if the root word ends in d, de or se.\nFor example, the word decide becomes decision.\nThe -ssion suffix is often used if the root word ends in ss or mit.\nFor example, the word admit becomes admission.\nThe -cian suffix is often used if the root word ends in c or cs. \nFor example, the word electric becomes electrician.\nIt is mostly used to indicate a profession – e.g. magician.\nIt is important to note that th',     'hlWords':['calculation', 'election', 'confusion', 'division', 'vacation', 'creation', 'explosion', 'injection', 'invasion', 'selection']},
