    {'id':'y4-t1-w4-l1','year':'Y4','term':'T1',     'week':4,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':'Sequence 1','lesson':'Lesson 1',     'focus':'prefixes',     'explanation':'Prefixes are units of meaning added to the beginning of a root word in order to change its meaning.\nThe un- prefix usually means ‘not’.\nFor example, the word unhappy means not happy.\nIt can, in some cases, mean to ‘reverse’ something.\nFor example, the word unlock means to reverse locking something.\nThe dis- prefix usually means ‘the opposite of’ or ‘not’.\nFor example, the word disobey is the opposite of the word ‘obey’ and means to not obey.\nIt can, in some cases, mean ‘apart’ or ‘away’.\nFor example, the word disappear is the opposite of appear – but it also shows that something has gone away',     'hlWords':['unwell', 'untrue', 'unclear', 'mismatch', 'miscount', 'mislead', 'disorder', 'disagree', 'disappear', 'misplace']},
