    {'id':'y4-t1-w5-l1','year':'Y4','term':'T1',     'week':5,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':'Sequence 1','lesson':'Lesson 4',     'focus':'prefixes',     'explanation':'Prefixes are units of meaning added to the beginning of a root word in order to change its meaning.\nThe prefixes in- / il- / im- / ir- all have the same meaning – they mean ‘not’.\nThe in- prefix is the most common.\nHowever, it is important to consider the root word when deciding which prefix to apply.\nThe il- prefix is applied when the root word begins with the letter ‘l’.\nFor example, the word ‘legal’ becomes ‘illegal’.\nThe ir- prefix is applied when the root word begins with the letter ‘r’.\nFor example, the word ‘rational’ becomes ‘irrational’.\nThe im- prefix is applied when the root word b',     'hlWords':['inactive', 'insecure', 'invisible', 'incomplete', 'impersonal', 'immobile', 'irrelevant', 'irregular', 'illegible', 'illogical']},
