    {'id':'y4-t2-w1-l1','year':'Y4','term':'T2',     'week':1,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':'Sequence 2','lesson':'Lesson 1',     'focus':'homophones',     'explanation':'Homophones are words that sound the same but have different spellings and meanings.\nyour / you’re\nThe word your is possessive. It indicates that something belongs to you.\nPlease hand in your book.\nThe word you’re is a contraction of you are. \nI know that you’re trying hard.\nthere / their / they’re\nThe word there refers to a place or can be used to point out something.\nPut your shoes over there.\nThe word their shows possession. It indicates that someone owns something.\nWe visited their house yesterday.\nThe word they’re is a contraction of they are.\nThey told me they’re going to be late.\nof / o',     'hlWords':['your', "you're", 'your', "you're", 'your', "you're", 'your', "you're", 'your', "you're"]},
    {'id':'y4-t2-w1-l2','year':'Y4','term':'T2',     'week':1,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':'Sequence 2','lesson':'Lesson 2',     'focus':'homophones',     'explanation':'Homophones are words that sound the same but have different spellings and meanings.\nyour / you’re\nThe word your is possessive. It indicates that something belongs to you.\nPlease hand in your book.\nThe word you’re is a contraction of you are. \nI know that you’re trying hard.\nthere / their / they’re\nThe word there refers to a place or can be used to point out something.\nPut your shoes over there.\nThe word their shows possession. It indicates that someone owns something.\nWe visited their house yesterday.\nThe word they’re is a contraction of they are.\nThey told me they’re going to be late.\nof / o',     'hlWords':['there', 'their', "they're", 'there', 'their', "they're", 'there', 'their', "they're", 'there']},
    {'id':'y4-t2-w1-l3','year':'Y4','term':'T2',     'week':1,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':'Sequence 2','lesson':'Lesson 3',     'focus':'homophones',     'explanation':'Homophones are words that sound the same but have different spellings and meanings.\nyour / you’re\nThe word your is possessive. It indicates that something belongs to you.\nPlease hand in your book.\nThe word you’re is a contraction of you are. \nI know that you’re trying hard.\nthere / their / they’re\nThe word there refers to a place or can be used to point out something.\nPut your shoes over there.\nThe word their shows possession. It indicates that someone owns something.\nWe visited their house yesterday.\nThe word they’re is a contraction of they are.\nThey told me they’re going to be late.\nof / o',     'hlWords':['of', 'off', 'of', 'off', 'of', 'off', 'of', 'off', 'of', 'off']},
    {'id':'y4-t2-w2-l1','year':'Y4','term':'T2',     'week':2,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':'Sequence 2','lesson':'Lesson 4',     'focus':'homophones',     'explanation':'Homophones are words that sound the same but have different spellings and meanings.\nbreak / brake\nThe word break refers to something being separated into pieces or a pause between two things.\nIt can be used as a noun or a verb.\nLet’s take a short break. (noun)\nHe managed to break the window. (verb)\nThe word brake refers to a device that slows something down.\nIt can be used as a noun or a verb.\nPress the brake before you reach the red light. (noun)\nWhen a cat ran into the road, she had to brake suddenly. (verb)',     'hlWords':['break', 'brake', 'break', 'brake', 'break', 'brake', 'break', 'brake', 'break', 'brake']},
    {'id':'y4-t2-w2-l2','year':'Y4','term':'T2',     'week':2,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':'Sequence 2','lesson':'Lesson 5',     'focus':'homophones',     'explanation':'Homophones are words that sound the same but have different spellings and meanings.\npiece / peace\nThe word piece refers to a single part of something.\nIt is a noun. It often follows words like ‘single’, ‘a’ or ‘one’.\nHe had lost one piece of the puzzle.\nThe word peace refers to a state of calm (free from conflict).\nIt is a noun. It is often used in the context of a feeling (including a feeling between places).\nShe is often at peace when meditating.',     'hlWords':['piece', 'peace', 'piece', 'peace', 'piece', 'peace', 'piece', 'peace', 'piece', 'peace']},
    {'id':'y4-t2-w2-l3','year':'Y4','term':'T2',     'week':2,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':'Sequence 2','lesson':'Lesson 6',     'focus':'homophones',     'explanation':'Homophones are words that sound the same but have different spellings and meanings.\nrain / reign / rein\nThe word rain refers to water falling from the sky.\nThe rain made the garden wet.\nThe word reign means to rule as a king or queen.\nThe king’s reign lasted twenty years.\nThe word rein refers to controlling something (often a horse with the use of a strap).\nShe pulled on the rein to stop the horse.',     'hlWords':['rain', 'reign', 'rein', 'rain', 'reign', 'rein', 'rain', 'reign', 'rein', 'rain']},
    {'id':'y4-t2-w3-l1','year':'Y4','term':'T2',     'week':3,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':'Sequence 2','lesson':'Lesson 7',     'focus':'homophones',     'explanation':'Homophones are words that sound the same but have different spellings and meanings.\nexcept / accept\nThe word accept means to take something that is offered (or agree with something).\nI would like you to accept my invitation.\nThe word except means ‘not including’ – it shows that something is different or not included.\nI like all vegetables except broccoli.',     'hlWords':['accept', 'except', 'accept', 'except', 'accept', 'except', 'accept', 'except', 'accept', 'except']},
    {'id':'y4-t2-w3-l2','year':'Y4','term':'T2',     'week':3,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':'Sequence 2','lesson':'Lesson 8',     'focus':'homophones',     'explanation':'Homophones are words that sound the same but have different spellings and meanings.\nweather / whether\nThe word weather refers to the condition of the sky (e.g. sunny/cloudy/rainy).\nThe weather is very cold today.\nThe word whether is used to express doubt or a choice.\nI don’t know whether to wear my coat.',     'hlWords':['weather', 'whether', 'weather', 'whether', 'weather', 'whether', 'weather', 'whether', 'weather', 'whether']},
    {'id':'y4-t2-w3-l3','year':'Y4','term':'T2',     'week':3,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':'Sequence 2','lesson':'Lesson 9',     'focus':'homophones',     'explanation':'Homophones are words that sound the same but have different spellings and meanings.\neffect / affect\nThe word effect refers to the result or impact of something. \nToo much sugar can effect your health.\nOften, the word ‘effect’ appears in a sentence containing had/have/has.\nThe word affect is used to show an influence or change.\nBad news can affect your mood.',     'hlWords':['affect', 'effect', 'affect', 'effect', 'affect', 'effect', 'affect', 'effect', 'affect', 'effect']},
    {'id':'y4-t2-w4-l1','year':'Y4','term':'T2',     'week':4,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':'Sequence 3','lesson':'Lesson 1',     'focus':'words ending sure/ture',     'explanation':'The -sure ending sounds like /ʒə/ (which sounds like zhuh). \nThis means that it makes a soft ‘z’ sound (ʒ) followed by the schwa (ə) that sounds like ‘uh’.\nExamples of words ending in -sure include measure, treasure, leisure and enclosure.\nThe -ture ending sounds like /tʃə/ (which sounds like chuh).\nThis means that it makes the ‘ch’ sound (tʃ) followed by the schwa (ə) that sounds like ‘uh’.\nExamples of words ending in –ture include picture, adventure, structure and creature.\nThere is not a clear rule to follow for these endings – but the sounds they form are clearly different so oral pronunc',     'hlWords':['measure', 'leisure', 'enclosure', 'fracture', 'lecture', 'structure', 'capture', 'adventure', 'texture', 'treasure']},
