    {'id':'y4-t6-w4-l3','year':'Y4','term':'T6',     'week':4,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':'Mastery 5','lesson':'Lesson 3',     'focus':'plural apostrophes',     'explanation':'Apostrophes can be used for two reasons: contractions and possession.\nWhen we use apostrophes for possession, we need to consider who the ‘owner’ is.\nI borrowed the teacher’s book.\nIn this sentence, the book is ‘owned’ by the teacher.  \nTherefore, we place the apostrophe in the word teacher’s.\nThe apostrophe is placed before the letter ‘s’ to show that one person has possession – this is known as singular\npossession.\nI borrowed the teachers’ books.\nIn this sentence, the books are ‘owned’ by multiple teachers.\nThe apostrophe is placed after the letter ‘s’. This shows that more than one person',     'hlWords':['installation', 'consultation', 'restoration', 'continuation', 'confrontation', 'expectation', 'conservation', 'adaptation', 'invitation', 'information']},
    {'id':'y4-t6-w5-l1','year':'Y4','term':'T6',     'week':5,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':'Mastery 6','lesson':'Lesson 1',     'focus':'the -ation suffix',     'explanation':'The -ation suffix is usually used to turn a verb into a noun.\nFor example, the verb inform becomes information (noun).\nFor most words ending in a consonant, the -ation suffix is simply applied.\nFor example, the word adapt becomes adaptation.\nWhen the root words end in e, remove the e before applying the -ation suffix.\nFor example, the word prepare becomes preparation.',     'hlWords':['league', 'plaque', 'plague', 'mosque', 'vague', 'unique', 'dialogue', 'technique', 'fatigue', 'antique']},
    {'id':'y4-t6-w5-l2','year':'Y4','term':'T6',     'week':5,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':'Mastery 6','lesson':'Lesson 2',     'focus':'the -ation suffix',     'explanation':'The -ation suffix is usually used to turn a verb into a noun.\nFor example, the verb inform becomes information (noun).\nFor most words ending in a consonant, the -ation suffix is simply applied.\nFor example, the word adapt becomes adaptation.\nWhen the root words end in e, remove the e before applying the -ation suffix.\nFor example, the word prepare becomes preparation.',     'hlWords':['grotesque', 'synagogue', 'meringue', 'cheque', 'rogue', 'tongue', 'colleague', 'catalogue', 'intrigue', 'boutique']},
    {'id':'y4-t6-w5-l3','year':'Y4','term':'T6',     'week':5,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':'Mastery 6','lesson':'Lesson 3',     'focus':'the -ation suffix',     'explanation':'The -ation suffix is usually used to turn a verb into a noun.\nFor example, the verb inform becomes information (noun).\nFor most words ending in a consonant, the -ation suffix is simply applied.\nFor example, the word adapt becomes adaptation.\nWhen the root words end in e, remove the e before applying the -ation suffix.\nFor example, the word prepare becomes preparation.',     'hlWords':['technique', 'monologue', 'unique', 'catalogue', 'mosque', 'fatigue', 'intrigue', 'cheque', 'colleague', 'critique']},
    {'id':'y5-t1-w1-l1','year':'Y5','term':'T1',     'week':1,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':'Revisit','lesson':'Lesson 1',     'focus':'prefixes',     'explanation':'Prefixes are units of meaning added to the beginning of a root word in order to change its meaning.\nThe un- prefix usually means ‘not’.\nFor example, the word unhappy means not happy.\nIt can, in some cases, mean to ‘reverse’ something.\nFor example, the word unlock means to reverse locking something.\nThe dis- prefix usually means ‘the opposite of’ or ‘not’.\nFor example, the word disobey is the opposite of the word ‘obey’ and means to not obey.\nIt can, in some cases, mean ‘apart’ or ‘away’.\nFor example, the word disappear is the opposite of appear – but it also shows that something has gone away',     'hlWords':['unhealthy', 'disrespect', 'misbehave', 'mismatch', 'disable', 'unknown', 'disorder', 'misprint', 'unwanted', 'dishonest']},
    {'id':'y5-t1-w1-l2','year':'Y5','term':'T1',     'week':1,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':'Revisit','lesson':'Lesson 2',     'focus':'prefixes',     'explanation':'Prefixes are units of meaning added to the beginning of a root word in order to change its meaning.\nThe prefixes in- / il- / im- / ir- all have the same meaning – they mean ‘not’.\nThe in- prefix is the most common.\nHowever, it is important to consider the root word when deciding which prefix to apply.\nThe il- prefix is applied when the root word begins with the letter ‘l’.\nFor example, the word ‘legal’ becomes ‘illegal’.\nThe ir- prefix is applied when the root word begins with the letter ‘r’.\nFor example, the word ‘rational’ becomes ‘irrational’.\nThe im- prefix is applied when the root word b',     'hlWords':['infrequent', 'illiterate', 'impersonal', 'irrational', 'incomplete', 'immobile', 'illogical', 'imperfect', 'insensitive', 'impolite']},
    {'id':'y5-t1-w1-l3','year':'Y5','term':'T1',     'week':1,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':'Revisit','lesson':'Lesson 3',     'focus':'prefixes',     'explanation':'Prefixes are units of meaning added to the beginning of a root word in order to change its meaning.\nThese prefixes are usually added with no change to the root word.\nThe prefix re- means again.\nFor example, the word rewrite means to write something again.\nThe prefix sub- means under.\nFor example, the word submarine means a vessel that travels under water.\nThe prefix inter- means between.\nFor example, the word interact means communication between two people.\nThe prefix super- means above.\nFor example, the word superhuman is a person who is above average.\nThe prefix auto- means itself or own.\nF',     'hlWords':['autograph', 'internet', 'antisocial', 'submarine', 'rebuild', 'supernatural', 'autocorrect', 'supervise', 'reconsider', 'autobiography']},
    {'id':'y5-t1-w2-l1','year':'Y5','term':'T1',     'week':2,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':'Revisit','lesson':'Lesson 4',     'focus':'words ending in -sure/-ture',     'explanation':'When a word ends in the /ʒə/ sound (‘zh-uh’), we use the spelling -sure.\nExamples of these words include measure, treasure and enclosure.\nWhen a word ends in the /tʃə/ sound (‘ch-uh’), we use the spelling -ture.\nExamples of these words include picture, nature and furniture.\nIt is also worthwhile noting that the -ture ending is often the ending used after a long vowel sound.\nAn example of this would be the word creature – where the ‘ea’ grapheme makes the long e sound.\nThe -ture ending is also more commonly used than the -sure ending.\nIt is important to note that the -ture ending sounds the sa',     'hlWords':['treasure', 'fracture', 'vulture', 'capture', 'composure', 'structure', 'adventure', 'enclosure', 'measure', 'creature']},
    {'id':'y5-t1-w2-l2','year':'Y5','term':'T1',     'week':2,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':'Revisit','lesson':'Lesson 5',     'focus':'the ‘uh’ sound spelt ‘ou’',     'explanation':'In some words, the /ʌ/ (‘uh’ or short u) sound is spelt ‘ou’.\nMany of these words have come from French or Middle English origin when ‘ou’ was a common spelling.\nThe words with this spelling pattern are an exception group.\nThis means that there are no clear rules for the application of this spelling pattern.\nInstead, children simply have to learn the spellings of these words.',     'hlWords':['touch', 'young', 'cousin', 'double', 'trouble', 'couple', 'country', 'courage', 'rough', 'tough']},
    {'id':'y5-t1-w2-l3','year':'Y5','term':'T1',     'week':2,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':'Revisit','lesson':'Lesson 6',     'focus':'alternative spellings for k, sh and s',     'explanation':'In words that come from Greek roots, the ‘k’ sound is often spelt ‘ch’.\nExamples of this include chorus, school and character.\nIn words that come from French roots, the ‘sh’ sound is often spelt ‘ch’.\nExamples of this include chef, machine and parachute.\nIn words that come from Latin roots, the ‘s’ sound is often spelt ‘sc’.\nExamples of this include science, scissors and muscle.\nThe ‘sc’ grapheme is usually followed by either the letter i or the letter e.',     'hlWords':['school', 'chorus', 'stomach', 'character', 'chef', 'machine', 'parachute', 'science', 'scissors', 'scent']},
    {'id':'y5-t1-w3-l1','year':'Y5','term':'T1',     'week':3,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':'Revisit','lesson':'Lesson 7',     'focus':'apostrophes for plural possession',     'explanation':'Apostrophes can be used to indicate contraction, which means two words being combined.\nFor example, when the two words ‘did not’ are contracted, the result is didn’t – the apostrophe indicates the \nomitted letters.\nApostrophes can also be used to indicate possession – both singular and plural.\nThe apostrophe is always placed in the word indicating the owner.\nWhen there is one owner (singular possession), we add an apostrophe before the s.\nMy friend’s mother baked a delicious cake.\nWhen there is more than one owner (plural possession), we add an apostrophe after the s.\nThe girls’ dresses spark',     'hlWords':["teachers'", "boys'", "dogs'", "players'", "fans'", "girls'", "coaches'", "sisters'", "parents'", "friends'"]},
    {'id':'y5-t1-w3-l2','year':'Y5','term':'T1',     'week':3,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':'Revisit','lesson':'Lesson 8',     'focus':'apostrophes for plural possession',     'explanation':'Apostrophes can be used to indicate contraction, which means two words being combined.\nFor example, when the two words ‘did not’ are contracted, the result is didn’t – the apostrophe indicates the \nomitted letters.\nApostrophes can also be used to indicate possession – both singular and plural.\nThe apostrophe is always placed in the word indicating the owner.\nWhen there is one owner (singular possession), we add an apostrophe before the s.\nMy friend’s mother baked a delicious cake.\nWhen there is more than one owner (plural possession), we add an apostrophe after the s.\nThe girls’ dresses spark',     'hlWords':["men's", "children's", "women's", "people's", "trees'", "teachers'", "students'", "leaves'", "parents'", "boys'"]},
    {'id':'y5-t1-w3-l3','year':'Y5','term':'T1',     'week':3,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':'Revisit','lesson':'Lesson 9',     'focus':'words ending in gue/que',     'explanation':'The gue and que endings come from French origins.\nThe gue ending forms the hard g sound at the end of a word.\nExamples of words following this pattern include league, fatigue and colleague.\nIt might be worth noting that it often follows a short o sound or a long e sound (made by ea or i).\nThe que ending forms the hard k sound at the end of a word.\nExamples of words following this pattern include antique, opaque and technique.\nIt might be worth noting that it often follows a long e sound (made by i) or a the letter s.',     'hlWords':['tongue', 'unique', 'mosque', 'technique', 'fatigue', 'vague', 'antique', 'league', 'dialogue', 'opaque']},
    {'id':'y5-t1-w4-l1','year':'Y5','term':'T1',     'week':4,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':'Sequence 1','lesson':'Lesson 1',     'focus':'words ending in -cious/-tious',     'explanation':'The –cious and –tious suffixes sound like ‘shus’.\nThey are usually used to form adjectives from nouns. \nThe adjectives formed usually show that something is ‘full of’ or ‘has the quality of’.\nIf the root word ends in ‘ce’, remove the ‘ce’ and replace it with -cious.\nFor example, the word space becomes spacious.\nIn addition, words ending in -cious can have related words ending in ‘city’.\nFor example, the word tenacity is related to the word tenacious.\nIf there is a related word ending in ‘tion’, we often use the -tious suffix.\nFor example, the word nutritious has the related word nutrition.\nTh',     'hlWords':['gracious', 'spacious', 'malicious', 'vicious', 'ferocious', 'tenacious', 'audacious', 'capacious', 'atrocious', 'conscious']},
