    {'id':'y5-t4-w3-l2','year':'Y5','term':'T4',     'week':3,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':'Sequence 5','lesson':'Lesson 8',     'focus':'silent letters',     'explanation':'In the final two lessons in this sequence, children explore other, less common, silent letters.\nThe silent letter u after the letter g – at the start of a word (e.g. guard).\nThe silent letter s after the letter i (e.g. island).\nThe silent letter h before the letter o (e.g. honest).\nThe silent letter b before the letter t (e.g. subtle).\nThey also revisit this rule:\nThe silent letter t often comes between s and le (e.g. castle) or precedes en at the end of a word (e.g. listen).',     'hlWords':['honest', 'hour', 'ghost', 'island', 'doubt', 'debt', 'subtle', 'guide', 'guess', 'guard']},
    {'id':'y5-t4-w3-l3','year':'Y5','term':'T4',     'week':3,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':'Sequence 5','lesson':'Lesson 9',     'focus':'silent letters',     'explanation':'In the final two lessons in this sequence, children explore other, less common, silent letters.\nThe silent letter u after the letter g – at the start of a word (e.g. guard).\nThe silent letter s after the letter i (e.g. island).\nThe silent letter h before the letter o (e.g. honest).\nThe silent letter b before the letter t (e.g. subtle).\nThey also revisit this rule:\nThe silent letter t often comes between s and le (e.g. castle) or precedes en at the end of a word (e.g. listen).',     'hlWords':['listen', 'island', 'castle', 'doubtful', 'guessing', 'thistle', 'honesty', 'guardian', 'soften', 'guilty']},
    {'id':'y5-t4-w4-l1','year':'Y5','term':'T4',     'week':4,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':'Sequence 6','lesson':'Lesson 1',     'focus':'ei after c',     'explanation':'In most words, the rule i before e applies when the two letters appear together.\n(Examples include believe, achieve and shield.)\nHowever, when the long e sound follows the letter c, we apply ei after c.\n(Examples include receipt, deceive and ceiling.)\nThe mnemonic ‘i before e except after c’ is often used to support children’s memory of this rule.\nHowever, explaining that this occurs when the ei is producing the long e sound after a c is helpful to \nensure that children can identify words that do not follow this pattern.\nFor example, the word weigh contains ei but not after the letter c. In t',     'hlWords':['receive', 'ceiling', 'perceive', 'receipt', 'deceive', 'believe', 'shield', 'achieve', 'conceit', 'retrieve']},
