    {'id':'y5-t5-w2-l1','year':'Y5','term':'T5',     'week':2,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':'Sequence 7','lesson':'Lesson 4',     'focus':'homophones',     'explanation':'Homophones are words that sound the same but have different spellings and meanings.\nfather / further / farther\nThe word father refers to a person with a child. \nThe father held his baby.\nThe word further means more. \nI need to think about that further before I decide.\nThe word farther refers to a longer distance. \nTheir house is farther down the road.\nheard / herd\nThe word heard is a verb. It is the past tense of hear. \nI heard a loud noise outside.\nThe word herd is a collective noun. It refers to a group of animals (e.g. cows or elephants).\nIn the field, there was a herd of cows.\nsteal / ste',     'hlWords':['father', 'further', 'farther', 'father', 'further', 'farther', 'father', 'further', 'farther', 'father']},
