    {'id':'y5-t5-w3-l1','year':'Y5','term':'T5',     'week':3,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':'Sequence 7','lesson':'Lesson 7',     'focus':'homophones',     'explanation':'Homophones are words that sound the same but have different spellings and meanings.\nIn this unit, homophones ending with the letter t are nouns.\nTheir corresponding homophones ending with the -ed suffix are past tense verbs. \nguest / guessed\nThe word guest (ending with the letter t) is a noun. It refers to a person who is invited to or visits somewhere.\nWe have a special guest visiting tonight. The guest checked into the hotel.\nThe word guessed (ending with the -ed suffix) is a past tense verb. It means you tried to answer something when you weren’t sure.\nI guessed the answer to the question.',     'hlWords':['guest', 'guessed', 'past', 'passed', 'mist', 'missed', 'wait', 'weight', 'mail', 'male']},
