    {'id':'y5-t5-w4-l1','year':'Y5','term':'T5',     'week':4,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':'Sequence 8','lesson':'Lesson 1',     'focus':'UKS2 word list',     'explanation':'In this sequence, children study words from the UKS2 statutory word list containing double consonants.\nIn this lesson, the words contain a double consonant after the letter a at the beginning of a word.\naccompany / according / apparent / appreciate / attached\nThese words do not follow clear rules and often contain exceptions to rules.\nThe focus of this sequence (in addition to identifying double consonants) is to identify trickier parts of \neach spelling and link the words to their meanings. \nFor example, in the word apparent, we can see the word rent. The -ent suffix is used (instead of -ant',     'hlWords':['accompany', 'according', 'apparent', 'appreciate', 'attached', 'accomplish', 'accurate', 'account', 'accept', 'accuse']},
    {'id':'y5-t5-w4-l2','year':'Y5','term':'T5',     'week':4,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':'Sequence 8','lesson':'Lesson 2',     'focus':'UKS2 word list',     'explanation':'In this sequence, children study words from the UKS2 statutory word list containing double consonants.\nIn this lesson, the words contain a double m after a short vowel sound.\ncommunicate / community / immediate / programme / recommend\nThese words do not follow clear rules and often contain exceptions to rules.\nThe focus of this sequence (in addition to identifying double consonants) is to identify trickier parts of \neach spelling and link the words to their meanings. \nFor example, the word programme ends with a silent e. \nIt is not part of a split digraph.\nAnother example is the word immediat',     'hlWords':['communicate', 'community', 'immediate', 'programme', 'recommend', 'commemorate', 'commence', 'immense', 'immerse', 'commentary']},
