    {'id':'y5-t5-w5-l1','year':'Y5','term':'T5',     'week':5,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':'Sequence 8','lesson':'Lesson 4',     'focus':'UKS2 word list',     'explanation':'In this sequence, children study words from the UKS2 statutory word list containing double consonants.\nIn this lesson, the words contain two sets of double consonants.\naccommodate / aggressive / committee / embarrass\nNote that the word committee also contains a double vowel (ee).\nThese words do not follow clear rules and often contain exceptions to rules.\nThe focus of this sequence (in addition to identifying double consonants) is to identify trickier parts of \neach spelling and link the words to their meanings. \nFor example, the words accommodate and aggressive start with a short a – but pro',     'hlWords':['accommodate', 'aggressive', 'committee', 'embarrass', 'unnecessary', 'occasionally', 'successful', 'possession', 'accelerate', 'millennium']},
