    {'id':'y5-t6-w1-l1','year':'Y5','term':'T6',     'week':1,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':'Sequence 8','lesson':'Lesson 7',     'focus':'UKS2 word list',     'explanation':'In this sequence, children study words from the UKS2 statutory word list.\nThe focus of this lesson is on words containing silent letters.\nrhyme / rhythm / twelfth / vehicle / guarantee\nThese words do not follow clear rules and simply have to be learned.\nHowever, spotting patterns, like linking the words twelve and twelfth can be helpful.\nMore regular practice of these words in children’s writing is crucial and can be achieved through \ndictation sentences.',     'hlWords':['enough', 'through', 'although', 'tough', 'thought', 'cough', 'bough', 'thorough', 'borough', 'rough']},
    {'id':'y5-t6-w1-l2','year':'Y5','term':'T6',     'week':1,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':'Sequence 8','lesson':'Lesson 8',     'focus':'UKS2 word list',     'explanation':'In this sequence, children study words from the UKS2 statutory word list.\nThe focus of this lesson is on words containing silent letters – or letters that are ‘dropped’ when spoken \naloud.\nbargain / leisure / shoulder / category / cemetery\nThese words do not follow clear rules and simply have to be learned.\nHowever, spotting patterns, like breaking the word bargain into bar and gain can be helpful.\nMore regular practice of these words in children’s writing is crucial and can be achieved through \ndictation sentences.',     'hlWords':['cough', 'drought', 'thorough', 'throughout', 'fought', 'bought', 'brought', 'plough', 'dough', 'thought']},
    {'id':'y5-t6-w1-l3','year':'Y5','term':'T6',     'week':1,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':'Sequence 8','lesson':'Lesson 9',     'focus':'UKS2 word list',     'explanation':'In this sequence, children study words from the UKS2 statutory word list.\nThe focus of this lesson is on words containing alternative sounds / graphemes.\nthorough / neighbour / symbol / muscle / physical\nThese words do not follow clear rules and simply have to be learned.\nthorough – The uh sound is represented by the letter o and the ough quadgraph.\nneighbour – The long a sound is represented by the eigh quadgraph. The er sound is represented by the our\ngrapheme.\nsymbol – The short i sound is represented by the letter y. The le ending is represented by the ol grapheme.\nmuscle – The s sound is',     'hlWords':['breakthrough', 'thoughtful', 'throughout', 'thoroughly', 'rough', 'enough', 'although', 'plough', 'through', 'doughnut']},
    {'id':'y5-t6-w2-l1','year':'Y5','term':'T6',     'week':2,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':'Sequence 8','lesson':'Lesson 10',     'focus':'UKS2 word list',     'explanation':'In this sequence, children study words from the UKS2 statutory word list.\nThe focus of this lesson is on words containing alternative sounds / graphemes.\nsincere / interfere / privilege / criticise / language\nThese words do not follow clear rules and simply have to be learned.\nsincere – The s sound is represented by the letter c. The ear sound is represented by the alternative ere spelling.\ninterfere – The ear sound is represented by the alternative ere spelling.\nprivilege – The edge sound is represented by the alternative ege spelling.\ncriticise – The s sound is represented by the letter c.',     'hlWords':['knight', 'knocking', 'gnarled', 'gnaw', 'wreckage', 'written', 'wrong', 'whisper', 'white', 'whip']},
    {'id':'y5-t6-w2-l2','year':'Y5','term':'T6',     'week':2,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':'Sequence 8','lesson':'Lesson 11',     'focus':'UKS2 word list',     'explanation':'In this sequence, children study words from the UKS2 statutory word list.\nThe focus of this lesson is on words containing alternative sounds / graphemes.\nachieve / ancient / bruise / persuade / restaurant\nThese words do not follow clear rules and simply have to be learned.\nachieve – The long e sound is represented by the ie grapheme.\nThis links to prior learning about ei after c. Here, the long e comes after a different consonant (h) so we apply ie.\nancient – The c / ci produces the sh sound.\nbruise – The oo sound is represented by the ui digraph. The z sound is represented by the letter s.\np',     'hlWords':['thumb', 'climb', 'condemn', 'autumn', 'assign', 'align', 'campaign', 'guitar', 'guess', 'tongue']},
    {'id':'y5-t6-w2-l3','year':'Y5','term':'T6',     'week':2,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':'Sequence 8','lesson':'Lesson 12',     'focus':'UKS2 word list',     'explanation':'In this sequence, children study words from the UKS2 statutory word list.\nThe focus of this lesson is on words containing alternative sounds / graphemes.\nforeign / yacht / soldier / queue / amateur\nThese words do not follow clear rules and simply have to be learned.\nHowever, identifying unusual spelling patterns can be helpful.\nFor example, the word amateur ends in the ‘ure’ sound spelled eur.\nTeachers should also recognise common misconceptions and address these.\nFor example, children may write solider instead of soldier.\nMore regular practice of these words in children’s writing is crucial',     'hlWords':['bristle', 'whistle', 'nestle', 'glisten', 'listen', 'knuckle', 'design', 'wreckage', 'fasten', 'written']},
    {'id':'y5-t6-w3-l1','year':'Y5','term':'T6',     'week':3,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':'Mastery 4','lesson':'Lesson 1',     'focus':'the ough grapheme',     'explanation':'The ‘ough’ letter string is a quadgraph, meaning it is a grapheme constructed from four letters.\nThere are not many words that contain this letter string and it represents a range of different sounds; \ntherefore, these words simply need to be learned.\nThe ‘ough’ letter string generally makes the following sounds:\n- uff (as in enough)\n- off (as in cough)\n- aw (as in bought)\n- oa (as in although)\n- ow (as in bough)\n- oo (as in through)\n- uh (as in thorough)',     'hlWords':['receive', 'perceive', 'conceive', 'deceive', 'ceiling', 'believe', 'achieve', 'retrieve', 'relieve', 'receipt']},
