    {'id':'y5-t6-w4-l1','year':'Y5','term':'T6',     'week':4,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':'Mastery 5','lesson':'Lesson 1',     'focus':'silent letters',     'explanation':'There are many potential silent letters that children may come across.\nHowever, this sequence explores some of the most common ones – and the most common positions in \nwhich they occur.\nThe most common rules are as follows:\n1.\nThe silent letter b often follows the letter m at the end of a word (e.g. thumb).\n2.\nThe silent letter k often precedes the letter n at the start of a word (e.g. knight).\n3.\nThe silent letter h often follows the letter w at the start of a word (e.g. white).\n4.\nThe silent letter w often precedes the letter r at the start of a word (e.g. wrong).\n5.\nThe silent letter n oft',     'hlWords':['rhyme', 'rhythm', 'twelfth', 'vehicle', 'guarantee', 'muscle', 'conscience', 'foreign', 'government', 'queue']},
    {'id':'y5-t6-w4-l2','year':'Y5','term':'T6',     'week':4,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':'Mastery 5','lesson':'Lesson 2',     'focus':'silent letters',     'explanation':'There are many potential silent letters that children may come across.\nHowever, this sequence explores some of the most common ones – and the most common positions in \nwhich they occur.\nThe most common rules are as follows:\n1.\nThe silent letter b often follows the letter m at the end of a word (e.g. thumb).\n2.\nThe silent letter k often precedes the letter n at the start of a word (e.g. knight).\n3.\nThe silent letter h often follows the letter w at the start of a word (e.g. white).\n4.\nThe silent letter w often precedes the letter r at the start of a word (e.g. wrong).\n5.\nThe silent letter n oft',     'hlWords':['leisure', 'bargain', 'shoulder', 'category', 'cemetery', 'muscle', 'foreign', 'conscience', 'rhyme', 'stomach']},
    {'id':'y5-t6-w4-l3','year':'Y5','term':'T6',     'week':4,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':'Mastery 5','lesson':'Lesson 3',     'focus':'silent letters',     'explanation':'There are many potential silent letters that children may come across.\nHowever, this sequence explores some of the most common ones – and the most common positions in \nwhich they occur.\nThe most common rules are as follows:\n1.\nThe silent letter b often follows the letter m at the end of a word (e.g. thumb).\n2.\nThe silent letter k often precedes the letter n at the start of a word (e.g. knight).\n3.\nThe silent letter h often follows the letter w at the start of a word (e.g. white).\n4.\nThe silent letter w often precedes the letter r at the start of a word (e.g. wrong).\n5.\nThe silent letter n oft',     'hlWords':['thorough', 'neighbour', 'symbol', 'muscle', 'physical', 'rhythm', 'sufficient', 'yacht', 'queue', 'foreign']},
    {'id':'y5-t6-w5-l1','year':'Y5','term':'T6',     'week':5,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':'Mastery 6','lesson':'Lesson 1',     'focus':'ei after c',     'explanation':'In most words, the rule i before e applies when the two letters appear together.\n(Examples include believe, achieve and shield.)\nHowever, when the long e sound follows the letter c, we apply ei after c.\n(Examples include receipt, deceive and ceiling.)\nThe mnemonic ‘i before e except after c’ is often used to support children’s memory of this rule.\nHowever, explaining that this occurs when the ei is producing the long e sound after a c is helpful to \nensure that children can identify words that do not follow this pattern.\nFor example, the word weigh contains ei but not after the letter c. In t',     'hlWords':['sincere', 'interfere', 'privilege', 'criticise', 'language', 'necessary', 'innocent', 'conscience', 'sequence', 'adjacent']},
    {'id':'y5-t6-w5-l2','year':'Y5','term':'T6',     'week':5,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':'Mastery 6','lesson':'Lesson 2',     'focus':'ei after c',     'explanation':'In most words, the rule i before e applies when the two letters appear together.\n(Examples include believe, achieve and shield.)\nHowever, when the long e sound follows the letter c, we apply ei after c.\n(Examples include receipt, deceive and ceiling.)\nThe mnemonic ‘i before e except after c’ is often used to support children’s memory of this rule.\nHowever, explaining that this occurs when the ei is producing the long e sound after a c is helpful to \nensure that children can identify words that do not follow this pattern.\nFor example, the word weigh contains ei but not after the letter c. In t',     'hlWords':['achieve', 'ancient', 'bruise', 'persuade', 'restaurant', 'believe', 'relieve', 'mischief', 'retrieve', 'grief']},
    {'id':'y5-t6-w5-l3','year':'Y5','term':'T6',     'week':5,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':'Mastery 6','lesson':'Lesson 3',     'focus':'ei after c',     'explanation':'In most words, the rule i before e applies when the two letters appear together.\n(Examples include believe, achieve and shield.)\nHowever, when the long e sound follows the letter c, we apply ei after c.\n(Examples include receipt, deceive and ceiling.)\nThe mnemonic ‘i before e except after c’ is often used to support children’s memory of this rule.\nHowever, explaining that this occurs when the ei is producing the long e sound after a c is helpful to \nensure that children can identify words that do not follow this pattern.\nFor example, the word weigh contains ei but not after the letter c. In t',     'hlWords':['foreign', 'yacht', 'soldier', 'queue', 'amateur', 'guarantee', 'guard', 'tongue', 'disguise', 'catalogue']},
    {'id':'y6-t1-w1-l1','year':'Y6','term':'T1',     'week':1,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':'Revisit','lesson':'Lesson 1',     'focus':'words ending in -cious/-tious',     'explanation':'The –cious and –tious suffixes sound like ‘shus’.\nThey are usually used to form adjectives from nouns. \nThe adjectives formed usually show that something is ‘full of’ or ‘has the quality of’.\nIf the root word ends in -ce, remove the -ce and replace it with -cious.\nFor example, the word space becomes spacious.\nIn addition, words ending in -cious can have related words ending in -city.\nFor example, the word tenacity is related to the word tenacious.\nIf there is a related word ending in -tion, we often use the -tious suffix.\nFor example, the word nutritious has the related word nutrition.\nThere',     'hlWords':['spacious', 'ambitious', 'infectious', 'cautious', 'gracious', 'vicious', 'nutritious', 'malicious', 'fictitious', 'suspicious']},
    {'id':'y6-t1-w1-l2','year':'Y6','term':'T1',     'week':1,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':'Revisit','lesson':'Lesson 2',     'focus':'words ending in -cial/-tial',     'explanation':'The –cial and –tial suffixes sound like ‘shul’.\nThey are usually used to form adjectives meaning ‘relating to’ or ‘having the quality of’.\nThe suffix -cial often follows a vowel.\nExamples include special, crucial and beneficial.\nThe suffix -tial often follows a consonant.\nExamples include potential, torrential and residential.\nTwo common exceptions to these rules are financial and commercial.\nBoth of the root words (finance and commerce) end in ce, which is removed before the -cial suffix is \napplied.',     'hlWords':['official', 'special', 'crucial', 'potential', 'beneficial', 'torrential', 'essential', 'residential', 'impartial', 'artificial']},
    {'id':'y6-t1-w1-l3','year':'Y6','term':'T1',     'week':1,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':'Revisit','lesson':'Lesson 3',     'focus':'adding vowel suffixes to words ending in ‘fer’',     'explanation':'This revisit sequence looks at two rules for doubling consonants before vowel suffixes.\nWhen a word ends in a short vowel sound followed by a single consonant, the consonant is doubled \nbefore adding a suffix beginning with a vowel.\nFor example, the word ‘map’ becomes ‘mapped’.\nThis is because the short vowel sound (a) is followed by a single consonant (p).\nWhen a word ends in ‘fer’, we need to work out whether that syllable is stressed – this means whether \nemphasis is placed on this syllable.\nWhen the ‘fer’ syllable is stressed, the consonant r is doubled (e.g. transferred).\nWhen the ‘fer’',     'hlWords':['preferred', 'preferring', 'preferable', 'reference', 'referring', 'transferred', 'transferring', 'inferred', 'inference', 'conference']},
    {'id':'y6-t1-w2-l1','year':'Y6','term':'T1',     'week':2,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':'Revisit','lesson':'Lesson 4',     'focus':'words containing silent letters',     'explanation':'This revisit sequence looks at words containing silent letters.\nThere are many potential silent letters that children may come across.\nHowever, this mastery sequence explores the most common ones – and the most common positions in \nwhich they occur.\nThe most common rules are as follows:\n1.\nThe letter b often comes after the letter m at the end of a word (e.g. thumb).\n2.\nThe letters k or g often come before the letter n at the beginning of a word (e.g. knife / gnome).\n3.\nThe letter h often comes after the letter w at the beginning of a word (e.g. which).\n4.\nThe letter w often comes before the',     'hlWords':['knuckle', 'wreckage', 'solemn', 'gnarled', 'knitting', 'bristle', 'honeycomb', 'climber', 'gnome', 'hymn']},
    {'id':'y6-t1-w2-l2','year':'Y6','term':'T1',     'week':2,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':'Revisit','lesson':'Lesson 5',     'focus':'the ‘ough’ letter string',     'explanation':'This revisit sequence focuses on the ‘ough’ letter string.\nThe ‘ough’ letter string is a quadgraph, meaning it is a grapheme constructed from four letters.\nThere are not many words that contain this letter string and it represents a range of different \nsounds; therefore, these words simply need to be learned.\nThe ‘ough’ letter string generally makes the following sounds – uff, aw, off, oa, ow, oo and uh.',     'hlWords':['dough', 'through', 'although', 'trough', 'drought', 'thorough', 'thoughtful', 'bought', 'plough', 'enough']},
    {'id':'y6-t1-w2-l3','year':'Y6','term':'T1',     'week':2,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':'Revisit','lesson':'Lesson 6',     'focus':'words with ‘ei’ after the letter c',     'explanation':'This revisit sequence looks at words that follow the traditional ‘i before e except after c’ rule.\nThis rule applies when the word contains the long e (ee) sound.\nWhen the long e sound is preceded by a c, the sound is represented by the ei grapheme.\nFor example, in the word receive, the ee sound is represented by the ei grapheme because it occurs \ndirectly after the letter c.\nWhen the long e sound is not preceded by a c, it can be represented by a variety of other graphemes –\nthe ones in this sequence contain the ie grapheme.',     'hlWords':['receive', 'perceive', 'deceive', 'conceive', 'receipt', 'believe', 'relieve', 'retrieve', 'thief', 'ceiling']},
    {'id':'y6-t1-w3-l1','year':'Y6','term':'T1',     'week':3,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':'Sequence 1','lesson':'Lesson 1',     'focus':'words ending in -ant/-ent',     'explanation':'The -ent/-ence/-ency suffixes are more common than the -ant/-ance/-ancy suffixes.\nThese suffixes are used to form nouns (e.g. emigrant) or adjectives (frequent).\nWe often use the -ent suffix after a soft c (innocent), a soft g (emergency) or the ‘qu’ grapheme \n(frequent). It is also commonly used for words ending in -er or -ere. The suffix -ent is usually also applied \nto words ending in -id (accident), -ide (resideent) and u (fluent).\nWhen a word ends in -ate (e.g. hesitate), we usually apply the -ant suffix (hesitant).\nOften, when a word ends in -y, the -ant suffix is used. The usual rule o',     'hlWords':['frequent', 'eloquent', 'subsequent', 'innocent', 'adjacent', 'urgent', 'diligent', 'negligent', 'intelligent', 'emergent']},
