    {'id':'y6-t2-w4-l1','year':'Y6','term':'T2',     'week':4,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':'Sequence 3','lesson':'Lesson 1',     'focus':'hyphenated words',     'explanation':'A hyphen is a short, horizontal mark that is joined to join words or parts of words.\n(It is different to a dash, which is a longer horizontal mark that joins parts of sentences.)\nHyphens are used in several different circumstances:\n-\nWhen the final letter of a prefix and the first letter of a root word are the same (re-enter) to avoid \ndouble letters\n-\nTo avoid ambiguity when the hyphen changes the meaning of a word (e.g. resign, meaning to quit and \nre-sign, meaning to sign again)\n-\nTo join compound words (e.g. well-known or three-year-old)',     'hlWords':['re-enter', 're-elect', 're-educate', 're-enact', 're-evaluate', 'co-own', 're-examine', 'co-owner', 'pre-existing', 're-open']},
