    {'id':'y6-t5-w2-l3','year':'Y6','term':'T5',     'week':2,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':'Year 6 Revision - Lesson 6','lesson':'',     'focus':'ei after c',     'explanation':'In most words, the rule i before e applies when the two letters appear together.\n(Examples include believe, achieve and shield.)\nHowever, when the long e sound follows the letter c, we apply ei after c.\n(Examples include receipt, deceive and ceiling.)\nThe mnemonic ‘i before e except after c’ is often used to support children’s memory of this rule.\nHowever, explaining that this occurs when the ei is producing the long e sound after a c is helpful to \nensure that children can identify words that do not follow this pattern.\nFor example, the word weigh contains ei but not after the letter c. In t',     'hlWords':['receive', 'ceiling', 'deceive', 'perceive', 'conceive', 'believe', 'achieve', 'relief', 'shield', 'piece']},
    {'id':'y6-t5-w3-l1','year':'Y6','term':'T5',     'week':3,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':'Year 6 Revision - Lesson 7','lesson':'',     'focus':'cious / tious',     'explanation':'The –cious and –tious suffixes sound like ‘shus’.\nThey are usually used to form adjectives from nouns. \nThe adjectives formed usually show that something is ‘full of’ or ‘has the quality of’.\nIf the root word ends in ‘ce’, remove the ‘ce’ and replace it with -cious.\nFor example, the word space becomes spacious.\nIn addition, words ending in -cious can have related words ending in ‘city’.\nFor example, the word tenacity is related to the word tenacious.\nIf there is a related word ending in ‘tion’, we often use the -tious suffix.\nFor example, the word nutritious has the related word nutrition.\nTh',     'hlWords':['vivacious', 'gracious', 'nutritious', 'audacious', 'spacious', 'tenacious', 'ambitious', 'cautious', 'ferocious', 'precious']},
