    {'id':'y6-t5-w4-l1','year':'Y6','term':'T5',     'week':4,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':'Year 6 Revision - Lesson 10','lesson':'',     'focus':'ant / ent',     'explanation':'The -ent/-ence/-ency suffixes are more common than the -ant/-ance/-ancy suffixes.\nThese suffixes are used to form nouns (e.g. emigrant) or adjectives (frequent).\nWe often use the -ent suffix after a soft c (innocent), a soft g (emergency) or the ‘qu’ grapheme \n(frequent). It is also commonly used for words ending in -er or -ere. The suffix -ent is usually also applied \nto words ending in -id (accident), -ide (resident) and u (fluent).\nWhen a word ends in -ate (e.g. hesitate), we usually apply the -ant suffix (hesitant).\nOften, when a word ends in -y, the -ant suffix is used. The usual rule of',     'hlWords':['frequent', 'emergency', 'hesitant', 'expectancy', 'contingency', 'complacency', 'tolerance', 'innocent', 'fluent', 'resident']},
    {'id':'y6-t5-w4-l2','year':'Y6','term':'T5',     'week':4,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':'Year 6 Revision - Lesson 11','lesson':'',     'focus':'ous suffix',     'explanation':'The -ous suffix is added to nouns to form adjectives.\nIt means ‘full of’ or ‘having the quality of’.\nFor most root words, simply add -ous (poisonous).\nIf the root word ends in y, change y to i before adding -ous.\nFor example, the word envy becomes envious.\nIf the root word ends in our, change our to or before adding -ous.\nFor example, the word humour becomes humorous.\nOften, if the root word ends in e, the e should be removed before adding -ous.\nFor example, the word continue becomes continuous.\nHowever, if the root word ends in ge, DO NOT remove the e (e.g. outrageous).\nThis is because the e',     'hlWords':['victorious', 'adventurous', 'advantageous', 'horrendous', 'rigorous', 'dangerous', 'poisonous', 'courageous', 'glorious', 'glamorous']},
    {'id':'y6-t5-w4-l3','year':'Y6','term':'T5',     'week':4,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':'Year 6 Revision - Lesson 12','lesson':'',     'focus':'ly suffix',     'explanation':'For most root words, we simply add the -ly suffix (because it begins with a consonant).\nHowever, there are some exceptions to this, where other rules apply.\nIf the root word ends in y, change y to i before adding -ly.\nFor example, the word happy becomes happily.\nIf the root word ends in -le, change -le to -ly.\nFor example, the word gentle becomes gently.\nIf the root word ends in -ic, use the -ally suffix (instead of -ly).\nFor example, the word magic becomes magically.',     'hlWords':['typically', 'mightily', 'subtly', 'probably', 'directly', 'dramatically', 'happily', 'gently', 'magically', 'frantically']},
    {'id':'y6-t5-w5-l1','year':'Y6','term':'T5',     'week':5,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':'Year 6 Revision - Lesson 13','lesson':'',     'focus':'tion / sion / ssion / cian',     'explanation':'These suffixes are pronounced like ‘shun’.\nThe -tion suffix is often used if the root word ends in t or te.\nFor example, the word complete becomes completion.\nThe -sion suffix is often used if the root word ends in d, de or se.\nFor example, the word decide becomes decision.\nThe -ssion suffix is often used if the root word ends in ss or mit.\nFor example, the word admit becomes admission.\nThe -cian suffix is often used if the root word ends in c or cs. \nFor example, the word electric becomes electrician.\nIt is mostly used to indicate a profession – e.g. magician.\nIt is important to note that th',     'hlWords':['reaction', 'progression', 'musician', 'division', 'expansion', 'operation', 'magician', 'selection', 'confusion', 'electrician']},
    {'id':'y6-t5-w5-l2','year':'Y6','term':'T5',     'week':5,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':'Year 6 Revision - Lesson 14','lesson':'',     'focus':'applying vowel suffixes',     'explanation':'When a word ends in a consonant + e, we remove the e before we add a vowel suffix (-ed/-est/-er/-ing/-y).\nFor example, the word move becomes moving and the word shine becomes shiny.\nWhen a word ends in a vowel + y, we simply add the vowel suffix.\nFor example, play becomes playing or played or player.\nOften, for vowel suffixes, when a word ends in a consonant + y, we change the y to i before we add the suffix.\nFor example, the word carry becomes carried and the word happy becomes happier.\nHowever, the exception to this rule is the –ing suffix. The -ing suffix is simply added.\nFor example, carr',     'hlWords':['hurrying', 'occupier', 'annoying', 'destroyed', 'replying', 'multiplier', 'identified', 'simplified', 'inspired', 'happiest']},
